WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.080
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes I wonder what it would be like to live in a borderless world. By that I don't

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:16.120
[Amit Varma]: just mean borders between nation states like the horrendous Ratcliffe line, but also borders

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:21.600
[Amit Varma]: of taxonomy and categorization, which divide people and ossify traditions. What would it

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:26.800
[Amit Varma]: be like to be an unbridled seeker, to be able to pick up your bags and go on a journey without

00:00:26.800 --> 00:00:31.520
[Amit Varma]: worrying about visas or passport controls, to enter into dialogues with people where

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:36.960
[Amit Varma]: your intellectual quest is your only agenda and barriers of birth and ethnicity and class

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:42.040
[Amit Varma]: and identity don't matter? Well, it turns out that a few centuries ago, a man today

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:47.480
[Amit Varma]: known as Guru Nanak did just that. He traveled to places that are today dispersed across

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:52.520
[Amit Varma]: nine countries, and he traveled not as a founder of a faith as we know him today, but as a

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:57.880
[Amit Varma]: seeker in search of truth and dialogue. Things have changed since then. Centuries have passed.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:03.000
[Amit Varma]: The brutalities of history have created walls between us, not just on land, but in our hearts

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.240
[Amit Varma]: and minds. In such a situation, I wonder what would happen if someone attempted to retrace

00:01:09.240 --> 00:01:22.720
[Unknown]: the path of Guru Nanak? Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics,

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:27.440
[Amit Varma]: politics, and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma. Welcome to The Scene

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:32.080
[Amit Varma]: and the Unseen. My guest for today's show is Amardeep Singh, who was for most of his

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:37.840
[Amit Varma]: adult life, a fat cat MBA busy being a corporate satrap. But then he gave it up at one point

00:01:37.840 --> 00:01:42.640
[Amit Varma]: to travel through Sikh sites in Pakistan or other Nanak Panti sites, and we'll explain

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:48.960
[Amit Varma]: the distinction soon, and produced two books called The Lost Heritage and The Quest Continues,

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:53.200
[Amit Varma]: as well as two documentaries on these travels. These will be linked from the show notes.

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:59.600
[Amit Varma]: He is now engaged in a hugely ambitious process, that of retracing the travels of Guru Nanak

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:05.760
[Amit Varma]: across what is today nine countries. This is all coming together in a documentary series

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:11.840
[Amit Varma]: called Allegory, a tapestry of Nanak's travels. Before I begin my conversation with Amardeep

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:17.440
[Amit Varma]: though, let's take a quick commercial break. If you enjoy listening to The Scene and the

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:22.320
[Amit Varma]: Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the show alive. The Scene and the Unseen has been

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:27.600
[Amit Varma]: a labor of love for me. I've enjoyed putting together many stimulating conversations, expanding

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:32.840
[Amit Varma]: my brain and my universe, and hopefully yours as well. But while the work has been its own

00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:36.920
[Amit Varma]: reward, I don't actually make much money off the show. Although The Scene and the Unseen

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:42.160
[Amit Varma]: has great numbers, advertisers haven't really woken up to the insane engagement level of

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:47.520
[Amit Varma]: podcasts. I do many many hours of deep research for each episode, besides all the logistics

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:53.680
[Amit Varma]: of producing the show myself. Scheduling guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:58.720
[Amit Varma]: and so on. So well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going, and that involves

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:04.000
[Amit Varma]: you. My proposition for you is this. For every episode of The Scene and the Unseen that you

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.360
[Amit Varma]: enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth. You can

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:14.960
[Amit Varma]: do this by heading over to sceneunseen.in slash support and contributing an amount of

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:20.800
[Amit Varma]: your choice. This is not a subscription. The Scene and the Unseen will continue to be free

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:27.880
[Amit Varma]: on all podcast apps and at sceneunseen.in. This is just a gesture of appreciation. Help

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:32.360
[Amit Varma]: keep this thing going. sceneunseen.in slash support.

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:37.200
[Amit Varma]: Amardeep, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Thank you Amit for giving this opportunity. Really appreciate being here with you.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:44.840
[Amit Varma]: Amardeep, you know, before we get started, tell me a little bit about your history and

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:48.840
[Amit Varma]: how you came to this because I was sort of, you know, when I first heard about this project,

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:53.760
[Amit Varma]: when we were both invited to the Vidarbha Literary Festival, a month or so ago, I presume

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:57.240
[Amit Varma]: you must be a professor of history or something of that sort. And then I look at your bio

00:03:57.240 --> 00:04:02.040
[Amit Varma]: and I'm like, wait, MBA from Chicago? And, you know, what's going on?

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:08.960
[Guest]: You know, life has its own ways of manifesting and taking you in different strands. Yes,

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:14.320
[Guest]: it's a non-traditional path. I'm walking a path of an unstructured life today, trying

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:19.680
[Guest]: to give it a structure. But then I've spent, like everyone else, good 25 years of my life

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:25.000
[Guest]: in a structured environment of the corporate world, right? And I educated as I was studying

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.080
[Guest]: at Dune School. I did my engineering, did a University of Chicago MBA, worked at Larson

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:34.640
[Guest]: and Toubro, Crompton Greaves, and then gone to American Express where I spent 21 years.

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:38.880
[Guest]: I was a regional head for Asia Pacific. All this period was a very structured life, nine

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:46.480
[Guest]: to five, nine to nine, you know, fall it whatever it was. You had hierarchy, structure, and

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:51.840
[Guest]: that's what you were doing. You were one piece in the big jigsaw puzzle, that's it. And then

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:59.520
[Guest]: something happened in 2014. And I walked out of the corporate world, actually not knowing

00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:04.960
[Guest]: what was going to happen in the days to come. But I walked out with a bit of an egoistic

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:09.400
[Guest]: attitude because my, in corporate world you do, your egos are very high and that's how

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:13.840
[Guest]: you succeed, right? And I walked out because my job was moving to Australia and I didn't

00:05:13.840 --> 00:05:18.120
[Guest]: want to go, period. So I thought, you know. You were based in Singapore, you are based

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:21.600
[Guest]: in Singapore. Yeah. So I started from India. I was in Hong Kong and then 20 years I've

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:26.040
[Guest]: been in Singapore. 2014, I walked away saying that I'll, at the peak of my career in the

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:29.880
[Guest]: corporate world, I'll get something else. But that was not meant to be. And when I was

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:36.280
[Guest]: going through that process, I would be lying to myself if I would say that I was not disillusioned.

00:05:36.280 --> 00:05:41.280
[Guest]: I was heavily disillusioned. The treadmill had stopped. I was still, my mind was running

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:45.440
[Guest]: at the same pace and I didn't understand what was happening. In fact, for a few months I

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:49.480
[Guest]: was lying on my bed just looking at, observing the fan going in the one direction and trying

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:53.200
[Guest]: to see why it rotates in the other direction visually, right? But you didn't understand,

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:59.600
[Guest]: right? But then now when I look at my life, we are now in 2020. So 2014, 2020, good five

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:04.200
[Guest]: to six years have passed by. I can rationalise now everything that has happened. But in the

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:07.800
[Guest]: moment there was no rationalisation. And the rationalisation now is that I'm walking on

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:11.480
[Guest]: an unstructured path, not knowing that the projects that are manifesting in my mind,

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:15.240
[Guest]: we're walking those paths and giving structures to those projects because you have to do an

00:06:15.240 --> 00:06:20.360
[Guest]: unstructured approach to get the data. The short of it all is that when I walked out,

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:25.320
[Guest]: what people don't realise is you just can't make a change one fine day. Because you try

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:31.480
[Guest]: and do the change in one fine day from an MBA engineering background to presumably you're

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:36.200
[Guest]: thinking I'm an historian. I'm not. Neither am I an anthropologist. Neither am I. I'm

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:40.800
[Guest]: a, I'm a theologian, right? Neither I'm a photographer, but I'm neither I'm a videographer

00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:44.800
[Guest]: or neither am I a filmmaker, but I'm doing all that, right? So how does that happen?

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:49.360
[Guest]: This change will not happen one day. If it happens one day, you will be totally disoriented.

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:53.480
[Guest]: You'll not be able to manage it. What people don't realise is the process behind it unconsciously

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:58.560
[Guest]: that was happening for 30 years that led you to this change on one fine day. And I can

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:03.300
[Guest]: now look back and see the structure in that, in that process. And I do give this message

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:08.240
[Guest]: to the youth is that I always say that don't follow your passion. Most of the people say

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:11.680
[Guest]: that follow your passion in today's world. I said, don't follow your passion. You will

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:15.480
[Guest]: not succeed. Create your passion. There's a huge difference between following and creating

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:19.280
[Guest]: because when you're following, you don't really have a structure behind it. You don't juice

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:22.040
[Guest]: it out. You're just following it because sake of following, you're just filling in your

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:26.560
[Guest]: gaps, right? When you create a passion, then you are going to become the passion. So when

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:30.420
[Guest]: I was in the corporate world or before that in college, I mean, I, I had this habit of

00:07:30.420 --> 00:07:33.720
[Guest]: just picking up something. It could be anything. I was picking up history and I was just kind

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:37.820
[Guest]: of juicing it out at the age of 17 years. I started reading history good at five to

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:42.520
[Guest]: six years into the reading of history for the regions that interested me was Punjab,

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:48.960
[Guest]: Kashmir, Afghanistan. I juiced it out. I lost interest. And then my corporate career started

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:53.600
[Guest]: and I got spiritually oriented. I delved into the scriptures of my own faith and then the

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:57.400
[Guest]: Sikh faith. And then I delved into many of the scriptures, juiced it out. Then I got

00:07:57.400 --> 00:08:01.360
[Guest]: into music, juiced it out in four or five years. I stopped at one fine day. I had this

00:08:01.360 --> 00:08:03.440
[Guest]: habit of just stopping at one fine day when I think the challenge.

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:08.600
[Guest]: And when you got into music, what do you mean? I started studying musicology and then slowly

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:12.680
[Guest]: started playing and understanding the Granth Sahib's, you know, rock systems. So the Indian

00:08:12.680 --> 00:08:16.900
[Guest]: classical system, then that led me to understanding the verses a bit deeper, but I just suddenly

00:08:16.900 --> 00:08:23.560
[Guest]: stopped it in five years time. And I stopped it at a time where I lost faith in the elusive

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:29.440
[Guest]: divine, the big power. I lost faith because certain events that were happening in my life.

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:35.720
[Guest]: And I always say losing faith is important because it allows you to then delve deeper

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:40.560
[Guest]: and then re-emerge with a new faith, which could be different. And I lost faith and I

00:08:40.560 --> 00:08:47.080
[Guest]: found answers in Kabir's verse in Granth Sahib. You know, Kabir says, Khalak, Khalak. God is

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:51.000
[Guest]: in creation. Creation is God himself. So what are you looking for? What is this quest of

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:52.000
[Guest]: yours?

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.640
[Guest]: When I realized that, actually, I just dropped dead everything and I picked up the camera

00:08:55.640 --> 00:09:00.160
[Guest]: and I started appreciating the creation itself. In a short time, my photography reached a

00:09:00.160 --> 00:09:04.440
[Guest]: certain level. And then I realized that many photographers contribute to magazines, but

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:09.440
[Guest]: they seldom are able to express their deeper insights, what went behind the photographs.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:14.160
[Guest]: So I started doing those travel writings with a deeper spiritual insights and then magazines

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:17.960
[Guest]: started picking them up. What I'm trying to tell you is then all these skill sets were

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:22.640
[Guest]: parallelly prepared while I was in the corporate world doing nine to nine job and I was doing

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:27.760
[Guest]: it unconsciously. And then came 2014 when I walked out because of a certain decision.

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:32.040
[Guest]: I thought, I don't want to move to Australia. I'll stay in Singapore, not realizing that

00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:35.840
[Guest]: that was not meant to be. The door was going to be shut. And when the door was shut, these

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:41.840
[Guest]: manifestations, these skills that I had acquired over layers by creating passions successfully

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:46.640
[Guest]: in a successful period, I would look back and I would find the next passion just behind

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:49.640
[Guest]: me and I would pick it up, you know, because you prepared yourself with one and you just

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:53.440
[Guest]: turn back and the next purpose is right behind you. You pick it up. You have built it up

00:09:53.440 --> 00:10:00.640
[Guest]: to a level where in 2014, I just thought, let me go to Pakistan. And the story starts

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:05.200
[Guest]: from there that just going to Pakistan leads to where I am today.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:08.720
[Amit Varma]: That's a fascinating journey. And I have some related thoughts. One, of course, is I couldn't

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:13.120
[Amit Varma]: agree with you more about follow your passion being a dangerous piece of advice, like on

00:10:13.120 --> 00:10:18.440
[Amit Varma]: a note totally unrelated to you. What I often find is that when people say follow your passion,

00:10:18.440 --> 00:10:22.520
[Amit Varma]: they have in, they fall for what is known as a survivor bias, that they'll see someone

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:27.400
[Amit Varma]: who is very successful, having followed their passion. And they don't realize that if it's

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:31.960
[Amit Varma]: a creative field, especially 99% of the people aren't going to be that person, they're not

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:36.560
[Amit Varma]: going to make it that far. And, you know, the cafes at Warsaw, which I frequent are

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:41.040
[Amit Varma]: full of people who have been struggling for years, even decades in the film industry here.

00:10:41.040 --> 00:10:44.520
[Amit Varma]: So I, you know, I kind of see it all around me, it's sort of dangerous advice to give.

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:49.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's also fascinating how and you've described this before on how you built up to where you

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:54.920
[Amit Varma]: are layer upon layer. And you've just described those layers of history, photography, sort

00:10:54.920 --> 00:10:59.800
[Amit Varma]: of musicology, and you know, which is also now another piece falls into place in terms

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:04.320
[Amit Varma]: of understanding your work, because in your documentaries, also, there is so much very

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:09.880
[Amit Varma]: interesting and apt use of music before we get to you know, you're going to Pakistan

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:13.120
[Amit Varma]: and how that journey for which the rest of your life seems to have been a preparation

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:17.680
[Amit Varma]: at that point, before we get to how that journey began, and so on. Let's take a quick diversion,

00:11:17.680 --> 00:11:22.260
[Amit Varma]: because you mentioned Kabir's phrase about, you know, the creator being in everything

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:27.640
[Amit Varma]: all around us. And you have also spoken in the past about how people have this misconception

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:33.920
[Amit Varma]: of Nanak's religion as being monotheism when it's actually monism. And what Kabir's phrase

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:39.160
[Amit Varma]: seems to express is also monism of a sort. Can you elaborate a little bit on that?

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:43.920
[Guest]: I think now we're getting into theology. It's an interesting point. I hear you. I hear you.

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:53.520
[Guest]: I mean, I was born with nothing in my mind. I was conditioned by my society, my parents,

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:58.960
[Guest]: what's right, what's wrong. And we all go through the process, right? And one fine day,

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:02.960
[Guest]: you start delving into the path yourself. And then you go to ask yourself these questions.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:07.040
[Guest]: Am I being, have I been taught the right thing all this time? And one of the things that

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:14.200
[Guest]: I realized in my journeys is that Nanak has not been really understood. Nanak wrote in

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:20.120
[Guest]: our Indic language. He's a master of languages. The Granth Sahib, if you see, there are, people

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:24.640
[Guest]: think it's Punjabi. Sorry, if you know Punjabi and try to read Granth Sahib, you'll not understand

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:30.120
[Guest]: head or tail. It's a composite of languages from Bengal when Jaidev is writing, Namdev

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:35.320
[Guest]: from Maharashtra is writing, Farid from Pakpattan is writing in Pakistan. It's Seraki, it's

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:39.840
[Guest]: Bengali, Sanskrit, it's Punjabi. Kurmukhi is a mere script, which we confuse, we don't

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:44.440
[Guest]: get into it. It's an amalgamation of many languages. Kabir from UP, Bihar area is writing

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:49.320
[Guest]: in it. So what I'm trying to say is that when you look at this whole composite, you find

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:53.480
[Guest]: this has been compiled in the time of the Bhakti movement. And Bhakti movement, there

00:12:53.480 --> 00:12:58.880
[Guest]: are two strands. One is from the Indic faith. I will not brand this into Hinduism or something

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:04.120
[Guest]: else because Indic faiths were bigger, right? So Indic faiths had many systems inside it.

00:13:04.120 --> 00:13:07.760
[Guest]: I mean, if you look at the Darshan Shastra of the Indian philosophical system, you know,

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:12.840
[Guest]: they have Sankhya, Yoga, Vedanta and so on and so forth. One of the branch is that everything

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:17.960
[Guest]: is one. And then there are many other branches, right? And everything has space. Sufism came

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:23.560
[Guest]: from Islam and got amalgamated within the Indus belt into what became the, Islam got

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:28.160
[Guest]: amalgamated and became the Islamic version of Bhakti, which is Sufism, right? So we've

00:13:28.160 --> 00:13:33.200
[Guest]: seen all this churning happening. And Nanak walks in this land of the Indus river. So

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:38.280
[Guest]: Nanak is talking in his verses about various languages. And then we have the Britishers

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:42.280
[Guest]: who come into the India and they give us the gift of English language and they translate

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:47.000
[Guest]: our texts. And we today, without delving into the deeper values of our own texts, have started

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.920
[Guest]: looking at translations to define who we are. You can do it. There's nothing wrong with

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:55.280
[Guest]: translations, but translations have limitations. So when I've gone through all this understanding

00:13:55.280 --> 00:14:00.400
[Guest]: of Nanak, I've not found a single book. I'm making a statement here. I've found not a

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:05.880
[Guest]: single book, say this, that has described in English what his philosophy truly was.

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:11.600
[Guest]: So Nanak is always described as he was the one who founded the monotheistic religion,

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:15.720
[Guest]: Sikhism and so on and so forth. Well, he didn't find, he didn't found anything. He just was

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:22.000
[Guest]: a man on quest, right? But monotheism is a concept that comes from Abrahamic faiths and

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.800
[Guest]: Abrahamic faiths being Christianity, Judaism and Islam, where they say God is one. It's

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:33.520
[Guest]: up there, right? There's a son of God, there's children of God, but children cannot be God.

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:38.680
[Guest]: God cannot be children. Like what Kabir says, God is in the creation, creation is God. It's

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:44.680
[Guest]: one ecosystem. Nanak says before Onkar, he writes a numeral one. Why didn't he write

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:48.580
[Guest]: two? Why didn't he write something else? One cannot as a numeral and he writes numeral.

00:14:48.580 --> 00:14:52.880
[Guest]: One numeral cannot be two or cannot be three or cannot be four, right? One means one. And

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:59.640
[Guest]: he's emphasising that this entire Onkar is one. We are one. Ek Onkar is one ecosystem

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:06.760
[Guest]: and that one ecosystem primarily means you are me, I'm you, we are all one. That is not

00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:14.080
[Guest]: monotheism. That's monism. And there's not a single book that says Nanak was the advocate

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:18.120
[Guest]: of monism. Because when you go down that path to understand Nanak, why did he put the numeral

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:22.880
[Guest]: one in the starting of the scripture of Granth Sahib? You understand, in the Granth Sahib

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:26.720
[Guest]: also there's a verse of Bhagat Ravi Das. I mean, I don't believe in any caste system,

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:30.400
[Guest]: but we need to actually bring that in because people, that's how they understand. Now Ravi

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:38.040
[Guest]: Das was a chamar, but yet he had profound verses. And he says, what's the difference

00:15:38.040 --> 00:15:42.320
[Guest]: between you and me? He's asking a question. Now it can be you Amit and me, or it could

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:50.400
[Guest]: be the divine in me. Gold and the bracelet, substratum is the gold. The bracelet is a

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:56.760
[Guest]: form or Jal Tarang, you know, waves on the base ocean. There's no difference. So Nanak

00:15:56.760 --> 00:16:02.480
[Guest]: is an advocate of monism. And that's the piece that has been not understood. I think that's

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:07.040
[Guest]: the piece that you were asking about. So Kabir voices the same thing. Ravi Das voices the

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:13.600
[Guest]: same thing. Farid voices the same thing. And that's why Nanak consolidated all their voices

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:17.520
[Amit Varma]: into the scripture that became Granth Sahib. And it's also, you know, picking up from what

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:21.680
[Amit Varma]: you said, it's also very interesting. And something I've discussed in previous episodes

00:16:21.680 --> 00:16:26.640
[Amit Varma]: with Manu Pillay and Madhvi Menon, among others, something that Sanjay Chakraborty has written

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:31.460
[Amit Varma]: a very good book called The Truth About Ourselves, which is that what we think of as Hinduism

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:36.400
[Amit Varma]: is actually Brahmanism. It's a very ossified version of it, just one belt of it. And you

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:41.160
[Amit Varma]: know, you correctly spoke of it as the Indic religions or the Indic traditions. And what

00:16:41.160 --> 00:16:45.840
[Amit Varma]: essentially happened was that when the British came here in an effort to understand this

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:52.280
[Amit Varma]: deeply complex universe that they had thrown themselves in of, you know, our subcontinent,

00:16:52.280 --> 00:16:58.240
[Amit Varma]: they created simplifying narratives, often with the help of the local elites, who obviously

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:03.840
[Amit Varma]: pushed what suited them. So you suddenly had a certain version of Hinduism, which is more

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:08.040
[Amit Varma]: like Brahmanism with an ossified view of the caste system, a very simplistic varna kind

00:17:08.040 --> 00:17:14.080
[Amit Varma]: of thing. Thrust in and the tragedy is that today we look back at that as if that is Hinduism

00:17:14.080 --> 00:17:18.560
[Amit Varma]: and as if that is a definitive truth. While the truth is that many of the Britishers who

00:17:18.560 --> 00:17:22.600
[Amit Varma]: created these narratives not only knew very little, but someone like James Mill hadn't

00:17:22.600 --> 00:17:26.800
[Amit Varma]: even been to India at the time he wrote what has now become a foundational text about India

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:34.360
[Amit Varma]: for us through kind of osmosis. And, you know, and in a sense, I find that that has also

00:17:34.360 --> 00:17:39.520
[Amit Varma]: happened in the popular consciousness with Sikhism, whereas people now think of Sikhism

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:45.080
[Amit Varma]: as something different from Hinduism or something completely apart and the truth is, and I found

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:49.240
[Amit Varma]: out the beautiful metaphor of this in the Indus belt in the Indus River, which you have

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:53.640
[Amit Varma]: described as a place where faiths melted into each other, you know, tell me a little bit

00:17:53.640 --> 00:18:00.240
[Amit Varma]: more about sort of the culture of that belt and how like you point out Sufism, Bhakti,

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:03.960
[Amit Varma]: what we'll talk about later as Nanak Manthi are all part of the same traditions.

00:18:03.960 --> 00:18:12.120
[Guest]: Yeah, so the Indic belief systems had the beauty of coexistence of varieties of thoughts.

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:17.120
[Guest]: Rather than giving my understanding of it, let me quote you the source because primary

00:18:17.120 --> 00:18:21.800
[Guest]: sources cannot be disputed, right? And I'll give you two quotes. Let's start with Kabir

00:18:21.800 --> 00:18:27.640
[Guest]: himself, who finds, I mean, Guru Granth Sahib, the Sikh scripture, is the largest repository

00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:33.960
[Guest]: of Kabir's writings. Bijak comes much later. That's the place which is the largest repository.

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:37.640
[Guest]: And Kabir says a very interesting thing. So you brought in the Indus. So I'm going to

00:18:37.640 --> 00:18:43.400
[Guest]: make a statement and bring Indus inside that. Kabir says, Hindu, Turak, Dohu ko samjao.

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:46.920
[Guest]: I'm explaining to both Hindu and Turak. Okay, so let's step back for a moment. Why is he

00:18:46.920 --> 00:18:50.960
[Guest]: not saying Hindu, Musalman, Dohu ko samjao? If he's talking about religions, then he should

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:56.160
[Guest]: say Hindu, Musalman, Dohu ko samjao. He's saying Hindu, Turak, Dohu ko samjao. Now today's

00:18:56.160 --> 00:19:00.240
[Guest]: context when I use the word Turak, the present generation immediately gravitates to Turkey

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:06.120
[Guest]: and I say, you just got it wrong. Turkey is a nation in the modern state, right? Turak,

00:19:06.120 --> 00:19:12.640
[Guest]: Babur was a Turak, right? Lodi was a Turak. Turak is a civilization that had its unique

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:18.120
[Guest]: characteristics that existed on the west of the Sindhu River Indus. There was a civilization

00:19:18.120 --> 00:19:25.360
[Guest]: that existed on its east. So Sindhu River was a defining boundary where two cultures

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:30.640
[Guest]: met. And of course, when you meet, you amalgamate, right? So what are the peculiarities of the

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:36.480
[Guest]: two cultures? Let's start with language. On the west of it, it's language from right to

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:44.780
[Guest]: left. On the east of it, it's left to right. 180 degrees. On the west of it, it's monotheism.

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:49.800
[Guest]: It's an Abrahamic faith. There's only one God and God cannot be creation. All right.

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:55.760
[Guest]: Come on the east of it. There's a potpourri of belief systems and everything can coexist,

00:19:55.760 --> 00:20:01.040
[Guest]: the Indic belt. And therefore people get confused. Monotheism is also a part of it, but it's

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:06.400
[Guest]: a subset of it. Monism is also a part of it. Multitudes are also a part of it, but that's

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:12.480
[Guest]: the Indic belt. And to understand that, let me pick up the second verse from Nanak himself.

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:21.800
[Guest]: He says, chhe ghar, chhe gur, chhe updesh. What is this six? If you delve into the Indic

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:26.720
[Guest]: Darshan Shastra, the philosophical system, the philosophy system of the Indian subcontinent,

00:20:26.720 --> 00:20:31.080
[Guest]: you'll understand the Darshan Shastra classifies our historically, the old philosophical system

00:20:31.080 --> 00:20:34.800
[Guest]: into six pillars, right? I'll not get into depth of it, but it's divided into six pillars.

00:20:34.800 --> 00:20:40.360
[Guest]: And it's a depth of study of six pillar system, right? Chhe ghar, there are six philosophical

00:20:40.360 --> 00:20:45.400
[Guest]: systems. Chhe gur, unke chhe guru hai. Chhe updesh. Each philosophical system has a different

00:20:45.400 --> 00:20:51.200
[Guest]: updesh. One is monism inside it. Chhe ghar, chhe gur, chhe updesh. Then he says, gur gur

00:20:51.200 --> 00:20:59.400
[Guest]: eko. Guru ka guru eki hai. Gur gur eko, ves anek. Ves anek hai. Then he says, he gives

00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:07.200
[Guest]: his final line in that. Chhe ghar, chhe gur, chhe updesh. Gur gur eko, ves anek. Baba je

00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:13.360
[Guest]: ghar karte keerat hoi. Karta jo, uski keerat, uski sifat sala ho. Praises. Chhe ghar, whichever

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:18.400
[Guest]: home, so ghar lakh vada hi tohi. Wohi ghar vada hai, wohi vada hai. So what he's saying

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:23.180
[Guest]: is accepting everything. Nanak is accepting everything. But what he's saying is a profound

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:27.560
[Guest]: statement of the bhakti culture that was emerging at the time when Nanak walked with Baba Farid

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:33.760
[Guest]: 250 years before him. Jaidev in Bengal, Namdev here in Mirashtra. They were all somehow getting

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:38.920
[Guest]: connected and they were the proponents of the bhakti system. So he's talking about,

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:42.160
[Guest]: in this Indic system, all was coexisting. That's what I'm trying to say. So he's talking

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:47.800
[Guest]: about Kabir who's defining a boundary and Nanak who's defining what the East was really.

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:52.940
[Guest]: Now when you put this whole thing together, Indus is a defining point. And on this side,

00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:57.440
[Guest]: you had many systems that could co-exist. But when you bring in boundaries around it

00:21:57.440 --> 00:22:02.600
[Guest]: and you bring in utilisation of a faith for the benefit, that's where Brahmanism starts

00:22:02.600 --> 00:22:08.960
[Guest]: coming by. Now Brahmanism has been opposed in the Indian context by many faiths or many

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:15.680
[Guest]: belief systems. Buddha did that. Mahavir did that. Kabir did that. Any bhakt did that.

00:22:15.680 --> 00:22:21.360
[Guest]: Nanak did that. So they were all opposing this ownership or that God can be only reached

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:27.000
[Guest]: through me, the concept of Brahmanism. So these Indic religions had a co-existence.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:32.640
[Guest]: And what the Sindhu belt basically did was when the Turki people started coming in, if

00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:37.200
[Guest]: you go to UP, you'll find where two cultures, the Hindi and the Islamic aspect, they use

00:22:37.200 --> 00:22:42.000
[Guest]: two words, Saptah and Haftah. Saptah becomes Haftah because in the olden times, in the

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:48.320
[Guest]: Persian, Sa is pronounced as Ha. So Sindhu became Hindu. When the Turkic civilisations

00:22:48.320 --> 00:22:52.760
[Guest]: came to the defining point of Sindhu, Sindhu became Hindu. On that side was a different

00:22:52.760 --> 00:22:57.960
[Guest]: culture which they were coming to assimilate into. I don't use the word conquer. There's

00:22:57.960 --> 00:23:01.320
[Guest]: nothing as conquering. Boundaries were not there. They were coming in to assimilate.

00:23:01.320 --> 00:23:05.040
[Guest]: There were tugs of war happening in terms of faith, in terms of assimilations. Many

00:23:05.040 --> 00:23:08.520
[Guest]: things happened in this thing. So they were assimilating here and they saw a different

00:23:08.520 --> 00:23:12.800
[Guest]: culture and that's why the word Hindu came in. And I will just say one thing that I've

00:23:12.800 --> 00:23:18.120
[Guest]: observed, you know, these are my own observations. When the earliest migrations of a lot of Punjabis

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:23.720
[Guest]: happened towards US, if you see the newspapers in the California belt, what they say, I'm

00:23:23.720 --> 00:23:27.400
[Guest]: not, I'm not saying Sikhs are Hindus or Hindus are Sikhs or I'm not going to do all that

00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:31.040
[Unknown]: discussion. I'm just telling you what I've observed. The papers say Hindus are coming

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:35.800
[Guest]: to America. Are they all Sikhs from Punjab coming in turban wearing Sikhs, right? What

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:42.160
[Guest]: I'm trying to say is that, yes, in the early days, the Hindu in the Indic belt was not

00:23:42.160 --> 00:23:47.480
[Guest]: a defined religion as we are calling it today. Today, it's become a defined structure. You

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:52.640
[Guest]: got to take the word Hindu as coming from Sindhu river as people on the Indic side living

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:56.320
[Guest]: here. I think that's something very hard to digest today when you bring it in. A lot of

00:23:56.320 --> 00:24:00.600
[Amit Varma]: people don't like it. And what strikes me is that on the one hand, there is a happenstance

00:24:00.600 --> 00:24:04.560
[Amit Varma]: of colonialism and the British trying to keep the narratives which are convenient for them

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:08.960
[Amit Varma]: because it fits in with their whole tactical policy of divide and rule. So it works like

00:24:08.960 --> 00:24:14.760
[Amit Varma]: that. But on the other hand, we also find this natural impetus within faiths themselves

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:21.080
[Amit Varma]: to sort of ossify in certain directions. For example, one, you've got the separation, this

00:24:21.080 --> 00:24:25.640
[Amit Varma]: separation in people's minds of Sikhism from the other broader traditions that they were

00:24:25.640 --> 00:24:31.160
[Amit Varma]: once considered to be part of. And on the other hand, you have, for example, the movement

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:36.320
[Amit Varma]: of Hinduism towards Brahmanism, which itself seems a political movement. And even within

00:24:36.320 --> 00:24:41.840
[Amit Varma]: Sikhism, you know, the Khalsa strand of it taking prominence and therefore some of the

00:24:41.840 --> 00:24:48.000
[Amit Varma]: other diversity with among Nanak's followers somehow kind of disappearing. Why do you think

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:53.000
[Amit Varma]: there is this tendency? Is it something inevitable? Is it going to happen to all intellectual

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:58.120
[Amit Varma]: traditions that you develop your own dogmas and customs and rituals and then they get

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:02.160
[Amit Varma]: ossified and then that defines a religion instead of being merely one expression of

00:25:02.160 --> 00:25:03.160
[Guest]: it?

00:25:03.160 --> 00:25:09.140
[Guest]: No, I think any faith goes towards defining of a boundary. That's a natural process that

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:15.720
[Guest]: happens, right? So there's no faith that's excused from it. But in the context of Nanak

00:25:15.720 --> 00:25:20.280
[Guest]: and his believers, one needs to put a bit of a historical context to it. When he walked

00:25:20.280 --> 00:25:25.440
[Guest]: the path along the Indus belt, so he travelled far and wide, but his major influence was

00:25:25.440 --> 00:25:32.440
[Guest]: in the Indus belt because I have walked the Indus belt from Kashmir in Pakistan side,

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:37.480
[Guest]: right down till Sindh, Balochistan, through Pakistan's Punjab and Khyber. And we can talk

00:25:37.480 --> 00:25:42.620
[Guest]: about my works later on, but I can confidently say probably in seven decades, I'm the first

00:25:42.620 --> 00:25:46.920
[Guest]: one to have walked so deeply inside, definitely more than 180 cities and villages. And I've

00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:51.760
[Guest]: seen strands of cultures that are still living there. I've been into Afghanistan, I've filmed

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:56.420
[Guest]: in Afghanistan and I've seen strands of surviving cultures. There are very few people left,

00:25:56.420 --> 00:26:00.560
[Guest]: but there was a thriving culture that was there till 30 years back. The war has disrupted

00:26:00.560 --> 00:26:05.160
[Guest]: everything and there are only about 850, what I call as the Nanak Panthis left there. The

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:10.320
[Guest]: only point I will try and make is the moment you move from the India or the Punjab of India

00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:15.280
[Guest]: and move towards the Indus belt in Pakistan and go down to Sindh, Balochistan, and then

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:18.800
[Guest]: go into Afghanistan, the one thing that you find in the people still who are living there

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:25.460
[Guest]: is that Nanak is an integral part of the entire non-Islamic society, which is a very interesting

00:26:25.460 --> 00:26:30.280
[Guest]: observation because when you look at it today, in the context of where the believers of Nanak

00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:35.680
[Guest]: are in India, so there were two strands and 47 people came here and for whatever reasons,

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:38.440
[Guest]: the boundaries kind of got restricted. A lot of people still believe in Nanak, they go

00:26:38.440 --> 00:26:41.640
[Guest]: to the Gurdwaras and all, everything. He's there in people's heart, but I don't think

00:26:41.640 --> 00:26:45.720
[Guest]: people are really understanding his philosophy, right? So it's just become another idol or

00:26:45.720 --> 00:26:49.520
[Guest]: another worship factor, but people aren't getting the depth of it. And then the Sikhs

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:53.300
[Guest]: have now become the only kind of perceived followers of Nanak. But when you go into the

00:26:53.300 --> 00:27:00.760
[Guest]: Indus belt, you find Dada Rewa Chand, Bansri Lal, Santosh Kumar, Santokh Singh, Ram Singh,

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:05.400
[Guest]: all followers of Nanak. And then you go into Afghanistan, the boundary of distinction between

00:27:05.400 --> 00:27:09.720
[Guest]: Hinduism, Sikhism, as we define in India, is not there. Now, when I look at that, so

00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:13.200
[Guest]: then I ask myself, I've read about these things because when you read the Persian sources

00:27:13.200 --> 00:27:17.400
[Guest]: after Nanak, before the emergence of Khalsa, I'm not trying to demean anything, Khalsa

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:21.680
[Guest]: emerged for a reason, there was a need for there, right? But till then, the Panth was

00:27:21.680 --> 00:27:25.800
[Guest]: in the Persian sources known as Nanak Panthi. The Persians are writing about the Panth of

00:27:25.800 --> 00:27:30.640
[Guest]: Nanak. Yes, in that Panth, there were many strands, many strands were there. Sutra Shahis,

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:35.280
[Guest]: the Udasins, the many other strands were there. And then came the Khalsa strand. There was

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:42.760
[Guest]: a reason for that. It saw its glorious chapters. But somehow, the factors in my understanding

00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:47.280
[Guest]: which have caused disruptions are a culture that was existing along the Indus belt where

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:51.720
[Guest]: the faiths were amalgamating. And I see that in Sindh, there are Darbars, and then there

00:27:51.720 --> 00:27:55.120
[Guest]: are Gurdwaras. And you see, you know, there's a lot of syncretic aspect coming in.

00:27:55.120 --> 00:28:01.440
[Guest]: 1947 is a point of deflection. I would say, if you take the whole landmass, what you see

00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:07.440
[Guest]: today as Punjab in India, is only about less than 5% of the entire landmass of the Indus

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:12.920
[Guest]: civilization where our forefathers came from. The Nanak's believers were right from Kashmir

00:28:12.920 --> 00:28:17.560
[Guest]: down to Sindh, Balochistan. And that 95% of the land went away. And one fine day, you

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:23.920
[Guest]: were thrust into a new land, and you got disseminated into Maharashtra, into Tamil Nadu, into UP.

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:29.160
[Guest]: My father from Kashmir landed into UP. And I've seen my own family's people, you know,

00:28:29.160 --> 00:28:33.480
[Guest]: the first obvious thing is you kind of, your generation becomes quiet because they've experienced

00:28:33.480 --> 00:28:38.040
[Guest]: a holocaust, right? You become quiet. Second generation becomes confused because you were

00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:42.880
[Guest]: quiet first. Second generation, the information is not passed on, you become confused. Third,

00:28:42.880 --> 00:28:46.760
[Guest]: it's lost totally. And some of them, islands get up and they start probing these questions,

00:28:46.760 --> 00:28:51.440
[Guest]: some of them. And I see myself as one of those islands. But when I look around, what I see

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:58.440
[Guest]: is that the dissemination of the people into a wider society resulted in a need for assimilation

00:28:58.440 --> 00:29:04.440
[Guest]: and acceptance. It's natural phenomena, right? You look different, your faith is different.

00:29:04.440 --> 00:29:09.080
[Guest]: Here's a different, there's civilizations along river belts. And the two major civilizations

00:29:09.080 --> 00:29:13.840
[Guest]: in the North India was the Indus belt and the Gangetic belt. Gangetic belt had a Hinduism

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:19.040
[Guest]: which was more, the Indus belt from the times of Nanak, Baba Farid and others, had moved

00:29:19.040 --> 00:29:24.440
[Guest]: towards more bhakti tradition. And that's where the caste system was being shunned.

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:29.080
[Guest]: The equality between men and women was being talked about. It was being talked about the

00:29:29.080 --> 00:29:34.120
[Guest]: equality between faiths. Nanak was saying, na ko Hindu na musulman. It is very differently

00:29:34.120 --> 00:29:38.360
[Guest]: inherently from the Gangetic belt. And then these people are thrust into this belt. Now

00:29:38.360 --> 00:29:42.480
[Guest]: you are on the fringe as yet in terms of faith system, because only a few years had passed

00:29:42.480 --> 00:29:46.760
[Guest]: by since Nanak and this uprooting happens. So as you land there, the generation starts

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:51.560
[Guest]: assimilating. I think that's what has caused a lot of moving away because people are confused.

00:29:51.560 --> 00:29:54.960
[Guest]: People don't understand. We've not done the passing of the philosophical message. That's

00:29:54.960 --> 00:29:59.400
[Amit Varma]: caused the distancing, I think. So, you know, I have a couple of follow up questions on

00:29:59.400 --> 00:30:02.960
[Amit Varma]: this. But before we get to that, you know, I've heard you speak about an encounter you

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:07.160
[Amit Varma]: had with someone from the Udasin faith in Bihar, which you said moved you greatly and

00:30:07.160 --> 00:30:10.920
[Amit Varma]: moved me as well when you told that story. So, you know, why don't you tell us?

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:15.920
[Guest]: Well, you see, there was there was many traditions that I said were in the strands in the Nanak

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:20.360
[Guest]: Panthi culture. And what's right or wrong, I will not get into because, you know, now

00:30:20.360 --> 00:30:24.440
[Guest]: I'm getting into the realm of faith, you know, and people have opinions. So to the viewers,

00:30:24.440 --> 00:30:29.240
[Guest]: I'll humbly request that don't pass judgments, because I'm only talking from what I've observed

00:30:29.240 --> 00:30:32.480
[Guest]: in my works. We've not talked about my works as yet. But so I don't know if people have

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:36.960
[Guest]: the context of what I've generated. But for my works, when I really walked the paths,

00:30:36.960 --> 00:30:41.200
[Guest]: and I observe a lot of things where it takes me and transports me back into time. And when

00:30:41.200 --> 00:30:45.680
[Guest]: they were in the Sikh history, when the Sikhs were facing the persecution, right, the Khalsas

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:50.000
[Guest]: were facing a persecution in the Punjab after the weakening of the Mughal Empire in the

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:55.680
[Guest]: period wherein Nader Shah invades, Ahmed Shah Dali invades eight times. In that period,

00:30:55.680 --> 00:31:00.000
[Guest]: it's a very, very dark period of Sikh history, because there was a reward for a Sikh's head

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:05.280
[Guest]: in the lands of Punjab. So the one who would swear to wear a turban and be distinctly visible

00:31:05.280 --> 00:31:08.960
[Guest]: had a reward on his head. Sikhs were living in jungles that time, they were doing guerrilla

00:31:08.960 --> 00:31:15.120
[Guest]: tactics, right. And in that period for the defence, the Sikh community cannot forget

00:31:15.120 --> 00:31:20.480
[Guest]: that the broader Nanak Panthi culture, the non-Khalsas took care of their shrines, their

00:31:20.480 --> 00:31:25.840
[Guest]: places. And I say it's not there in the Sikhs, it was ours. It was of the every strand that

00:31:25.840 --> 00:31:29.280
[Guest]: was there in Punjab, they were believers of Nanak. It was our collective composite culture,

00:31:29.280 --> 00:31:35.520
[Guest]: right. So the Udasi sect did do a lot of contribution. They managed the sites in the time when they

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:39.760
[Guest]: were not being persecuted because they didn't look like Khalsas, right. But the way history

00:31:39.760 --> 00:31:44.400
[Guest]: moved on and with the definition of the boundaries of who a Sikh is in the modern context, which

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:49.120
[Guest]: happened about 100 years back, it's a different topic altogether. But when you define something,

00:31:49.120 --> 00:31:52.560
[Guest]: right or wrong, I'm not going to get into that. But if you define something, you also

00:31:52.560 --> 00:31:57.680
[Guest]: define what you are not, you know. So defining has a negative side to it also. You also define

00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:01.280
[Guest]: who you are not. And when you start defining yourself in terms of black and white, you

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:05.920
[Guest]: also define who the others were not, right. I think that led to a bit of distancing. So

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:10.400
[Guest]: the over a period of time in 100 years, the Udasi culture moved away. And I was moved

00:32:10.400 --> 00:32:15.760
[Guest]: because I did meet one of the, in my filming of the Allegory of Tapestry of Guru Nanak's

00:32:15.760 --> 00:32:20.000
[Guest]: travels, I try and go into a lot of these strands of the past where the broader believers

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:23.600
[Guest]: of Nanak. To understand Nanak, you cannot understand him from Gurdwaras alone. There

00:32:23.600 --> 00:32:29.680
[Guest]: is space for Gurdwaras. But Nanak was travelling to Sufi sites, Hindu sites, Islamic sites,

00:32:29.680 --> 00:32:34.720
[Guest]: Jogis, where they were meeting. And therefore, you have to get into every place where he

00:32:34.720 --> 00:32:38.320
[Guest]: had been. So when I go into those places, I meet lots of different kinds of people.

00:32:38.320 --> 00:32:43.600
[Guest]: I make an effort to even go to Kanfatta Jogis, because he was having dialogues with the Siddhs.

00:32:43.600 --> 00:32:47.280
[Guest]: So I have to now in 550 years later on in his lifetime, I have to also interact with

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:53.200
[Guest]: them. So when I interact with the Udasi order in Bihar, I mean, this person interestingly

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:58.240
[Guest]: made a very interesting statement. He said, unfortunately, the way things have gone, we

00:32:58.240 --> 00:33:03.200
[Guest]: have been ousted from the faith. And he was hesitant to speak about Nanak. And I said,

00:33:03.200 --> 00:33:07.520
[Guest]: you know what, you've got Nanak all over your Dera. Why won't you speak about it? And he

00:33:07.520 --> 00:33:12.240
[Guest]: says, because we've been ousted. And then he said a very interesting statement. He says,

00:33:12.240 --> 00:33:18.160
[Guest]: all right, you make a judgment that we do this XYZ. Look into your own self. Don't you drink?

00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:22.640
[Guest]: Don't you do this? Don't you do that? And then you pass a judgment on us. And you've ousted us.

00:33:22.640 --> 00:33:27.520
[Guest]: And he says, had you not ousted us, you know, what my vision as a youth was, when I was a 15

00:33:27.520 --> 00:33:31.280
[Guest]: year old child, and I became an Udasi, all throughout my life, I was wanting to take

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:35.520
[Guest]: Nanak's philosophy into every temple of India, because it's the most important philosophy of

00:33:35.520 --> 00:33:40.240
[Guest]: oneness. But then when I heard him, I said, yeah, I mean, this guy is saying right. So if I don't

00:33:40.240 --> 00:33:44.720
[Guest]: have any religious objectives behind it, and no agenda, then just look at it objectively as to

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:50.240
[Guest]: what a person says, it makes you think. I'm no one to pass judgments on history, but it is what it

00:33:50.240 --> 00:33:56.640
[Amit Varma]: is. And you know, it strikes me looking at Nanak as a layman, it seems that rather than think of

00:33:56.640 --> 00:34:02.720
[Amit Varma]: him as the founder of a specific religion, which is distinct from all others, he seems to be more

00:34:02.720 --> 00:34:07.680
[Amit Varma]: a figure like Kabir, that even if you're not a follower necessarily, like I'm an atheist,

00:34:07.680 --> 00:34:12.800
[Amit Varma]: but reading Kabir always moves me. And I find Nanak to be a similar kind of figure. Is that

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:16.800
[Guest]: something you would agree with? Absolutely. All the Bhagats were the same. The thing is,

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:23.120
[Guest]: Nanak is absolutely, Kabir, Nanak, Jaidev, all of them are absolutely, Baba Farid, they're all

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:29.760
[Guest]: aligned. They're all profound Bhagats who were talking about oneness, trying to reform the

00:34:29.760 --> 00:34:38.560
[Guest]: society. You find appeal in Kabir, I find it too also, right? But then I ask many a times,

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:42.640
[Guest]: you being a Punjabi origin, how deep have you gone into Nanak? And we're not trying to compare

00:34:42.640 --> 00:34:46.800
[Guest]: two individuals, each to themselves. They're both powerful people, right? But how many times have

00:34:46.800 --> 00:34:51.840
[Guest]: you gone to Nanak? Now, I know the answer would be much lesser, right? And I as a follower of

00:34:51.840 --> 00:34:56.720
[Guest]: the Granth Sahib have delved into both. And I've always asked this question as to why would you,

00:34:56.720 --> 00:35:01.520
[Guest]: who was also from the composite culture of Sindh belt, the Sindhu river belt, the Indus belt,

00:35:01.520 --> 00:35:07.120
[Guest]: when your forefathers were actually revering the entire composite culture of the Granth Sahib,

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:12.080
[Guest]: where all these Bhagats were there, why would you not be reading Nanak so much? That makes me

00:35:12.080 --> 00:35:19.680
[Guest]: then question is that have we created a boundary so hard around the practices that Nanak has become

00:35:19.680 --> 00:35:24.720
[Guest]: inaccessible, his verses have become inaccessible? I think that's what has happened. Otherwise,

00:35:24.720 --> 00:35:30.400
[Guest]: there's no reason why Nanak's verse should not be sung by any other person who sings Kabir's verse.

00:35:30.400 --> 00:35:34.400
[Guest]: But rules, regulations and other things have made it hard now. Now, again, not trying to say what's

00:35:34.400 --> 00:35:38.400
[Guest]: right or wrong because we're getting into the realm of religion, but purely from his verses and

00:35:38.400 --> 00:35:42.800
[Guest]: his verses and his meaning, it's an unfortunate outcome that's happened. We can't blame anyone

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:47.440
[Amit Varma]: else but ourselves. Another sort of interesting thing that you were pointing out when we had,

00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:53.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, coffee before this recording is how Sikh history has often been elided and, you know,

00:35:53.920 --> 00:35:58.080
[Amit Varma]: not given adequate attention on either side of the border after partition. Tell me a little bit

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:03.360
[Guest]: about, you know, sort of why that has happened. So your question about history, just a bit of a

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:09.040
[Guest]: background for the viewers, is that the work that I've done, my two foundation works, is first in

00:36:09.040 --> 00:36:13.040
[Guest]: the book called Lost Heritage of Sikh Legacy in Pakistan. Second one is The Quest Continues Lost

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:18.800
[Guest]: Heritage of Sikh Legacy in Pakistan, in which I've mapped the remnants of the Sikh legacy across 126

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:23.920
[Guest]: cities and villages in Pakistan, across Baltistan, Kashmir, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Punjab, Sindh and

00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:29.840
[Guest]: Balochistan. Of course, I've been very passionate about documenting for posterity and that's why

00:36:29.840 --> 00:36:36.400
[Guest]: I've taken so much of risk to walk so deep inside, probably as a first person of non-Pakistan origin

00:36:36.400 --> 00:36:40.720
[Guest]: because my parents were from that area. I walked deep inside and I was able to get this documentation

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:46.320
[Guest]: done. But in the process, as I released my first book, I remember there was a history teacher,

00:36:46.320 --> 00:36:51.440
[Guest]: history professor sitting in the Delhi release, a non-Sikh, and she actually made an interesting

00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:56.720
[Guest]: point. And she said, Amarty, what you've just shared with us is absolutely right. And I,

00:36:56.720 --> 00:37:02.560
[Guest]: as a history teacher, can validate this because in the Delhi University, we only make a passing

00:37:02.560 --> 00:37:06.560
[Guest]: mention of the Sikh history, which is limited to Sikh gurus and a brief mention of Ranjit Singh

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:11.920
[Guest]: and that's it, brief. And you make me think as to why don't we delve deeper? And the answer to that

00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:18.240
[Guest]: question of hers or the thought of hers was, I said, I have thought about this myself too. And I

00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:24.080
[Guest]: feel that my community is a cucumber between the sandwich. And when I say my community, I'm talking

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:28.640
[Guest]: about the wider context, not just the Khalsa. Every Punjabi who got uprooted, every Sindhi who

00:37:28.640 --> 00:37:32.880
[Guest]: believes in Nanak who got uprooted, cherished the valour. Every family of Punjab would have the

00:37:32.880 --> 00:37:36.240
[Guest]: eldest son as a Sikh, right? They cherished it. That's why, right? They used to have them in the

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:43.440
[Guest]: past. So my answer to that was that we are a cucumber in the sandwich because I feel in India,

00:37:43.440 --> 00:37:49.200
[Guest]: not that it's officially said, but I feel we don't teach the Sikh history because 80%

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:55.440
[Guest]: of the glorious chapters churned in the lands that became Pakistan in 1947. And that is not our land.

00:37:55.440 --> 00:38:00.400
[Guest]: The great empire of Ranjit Singh and so on. 80% of the glorious chapters right up till Afghanistan

00:38:00.400 --> 00:38:05.280
[Guest]: border, Jamrod Fort where Hari Singh Nalwa died. After 1000 years of invasions, he plugged

00:38:05.280 --> 00:38:09.360
[Guest]: the further invasions through the Khyber Pass. No other invasion has happened thereafter. British

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:12.880
[Guest]: came from the other side, didn't come from Khyber Pass. But Hari Singh Nalwa is the deciding point.

00:38:12.880 --> 00:38:17.120
[Guest]: He plugged it. But that history doesn't find any place in India because it's a history that

00:38:17.120 --> 00:38:21.360
[Guest]: churned in the lands that became Pakistan, which is no more part of India. And when I walk in

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:27.520
[Guest]: Pakistan, the history books do not mention the Sikh history period. There's a silence around it.

00:38:27.520 --> 00:38:33.200
[Guest]: And I've seen the Punjab University books in Lahore, university books, two volumes. They talk

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:38.240
[Guest]: about the demise of the Mughal empire, the coming of Nader Shah Ahmad Shah Abdali, and then comes

00:38:38.240 --> 00:38:42.800
[Guest]: the advent of British. The entire period of the Sikh chapters is silent. And you look at that,

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:50.240
[Guest]: and you wonder why. And then I think it's because it's a period after 1000 invasion where the ruler

00:38:50.240 --> 00:38:55.600
[Guest]: of the state was not a Muslim. Now, it was a very secular empire. Ranjit Singh was a very secular

00:38:55.600 --> 00:39:00.400
[Guest]: person because more than 50% of his forces were Muslims. His foreign minister was a Muslim. So

00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:05.520
[Guest]: many brave generals of the Muslim faith actually died defending his empire. And yet he doesn't

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:10.800
[Guest]: find a mention because he is not a believer of the Islamic faith. So it doesn't find mention

00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:15.360
[Guest]: in Pakistan, it doesn't find a mention here. And that to me is the unfortunate thing that our

00:39:15.360 --> 00:39:20.160
[Guest]: community, therefore, I feel very passionately that if we don't write and protect our history

00:39:20.160 --> 00:39:24.400
[Guest]: in terms of visual remnants and other things, how will my next generation remember? How will we

00:39:24.400 --> 00:39:29.040
[Guest]: revive those art, architecture, cultural footprints from these various strands that I see across in

00:39:29.040 --> 00:39:33.520
[Guest]: the remnants in Pakistan? It's important to bring that perspective into these documentations so that

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:38.000
[Guest]: we don't lose those strands. And that's why I've been actually dedicating myself onto this path.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:43.600
[Amit Varma]: And this also sort of reminded me of, you know, you've written about how Guru Arjan

00:39:43.600 --> 00:39:49.280
[Amit Varma]: got Sam Iyam Mir of Lahore to lay the foundation of the Golden Temple at Amritsar. And how later

00:39:49.280 --> 00:39:54.160
[Amit Varma]: when Guru Arjan was sort of imprisoned by Jehangir before he was eventually executed,

00:39:54.160 --> 00:39:59.360
[Amit Varma]: Sam Iyam Mir and Vazir Khan got together to petition for his release, which kind of shows

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:04.400
[Amit Varma]: how, you know, there was so much sort of syncreticism in it and the differences between

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:09.120
[Amit Varma]: these religions and his people weren't as ossified and hard coded as it seemed to be today. And you

00:40:09.120 --> 00:40:13.200
[Amit Varma]: mentioned earlier families where the tradition was that, Hindu families where the tradition was that

00:40:13.200 --> 00:40:18.000
[Amit Varma]: the first child would be a Sikh. And I'm told my own family was one of those. So the practice stopped

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:23.280
[Amit Varma]: a generation ago, which is kind of fascinating. And all of this comes because of, you know,

00:40:23.280 --> 00:40:26.800
[Amit Varma]: that phrase that both of us have used, and I want you to talk about a bit more, which is

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:30.960
[Amit Varma]: Nanak Panthi. You know, you've pointed out, and we'll talk about your, you know, travels through

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:35.680
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan after this, but you've pointed out that people often have a misconception of how many

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Sikhs there are in Pakistan. The cookie cutter answer, as you've said, is 12 or 13,000 from the

00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:47.440
[Amit Varma]: 1500 who were left after partition. But your answer is that if you don't define the followers

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:53.200
[Amit Varma]: of Nanak as Sikhs, and you look at what you call Nanak Panthis, there are many, many more than that.

00:40:54.560 --> 00:40:58.800
[Guest]: Yeah, that's true. I mean, I'm often always asked this question. And I think Pakistan does not

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:05.200
[Guest]: understand this context of the Indus Belt. Sikhs themselves are ignorant of it now. So they tend

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:11.200
[Guest]: to see only the Khalsa count, people who are turban wearing like me, and I'm a proud adherent

00:41:11.200 --> 00:41:15.200
[Guest]: of the Khalsa tradition. That's my culture. That's my background. But I'm no one to decide who else

00:41:15.200 --> 00:41:20.160
[Guest]: is a believer of Nanak. So when I say the entire culture along the Indus Belt, all the Sindhis,

00:41:20.160 --> 00:41:24.960
[Guest]: all the Balochis have been the believers of Nanak. I mean, I see them all in Pakistan still.

00:41:24.960 --> 00:41:29.200
[Guest]: And what people don't know of is, you know, there are more than 250 Gurdwaras still operational in

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:33.280
[Guest]: Sindh and Balochistan, right? And so when you look at that, you say, you know, the entire culture

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:39.280
[Guest]: that's yet living there, and we are not recognizing them. So that entire belt is what we call as the

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:47.120
[Guest]: Nanak Panthis. My estimate is that there are over 800,000 Nanak Panthis still in Pakistan.

00:41:47.120 --> 00:41:53.120
[Guest]: When I meet Dada Rewa Chand in Sukkur in Sindh, and he shows me the translation of the Granth

00:41:53.120 --> 00:41:59.280
[Guest]: Sahib that he's done in Sindhi script, 24 volumes, although he's a small minority in Sindh of the

00:41:59.280 --> 00:42:03.600
[Guest]: Nanak Panthi culture. But that shows me the passion with which he actually believes in Nanak, right?

00:42:03.600 --> 00:42:07.360
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you've written about how Hindus in Sindh call themselves Sehdari Sikhs.

00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:13.520
[Guest]: Yeah. And Bansri Lal in Mingora, who manages the Gurdwara, by all definition of East Punjab,

00:42:13.520 --> 00:42:19.600
[Guest]: he will not be considered a Sikh, but he is a very devout Sikh. So I think that poses a question as

00:42:19.600 --> 00:42:25.280
[Guest]: to where our boundary today is and where it was. I consider myself very fortunate that having been

00:42:25.280 --> 00:42:29.600
[Guest]: born and being conditioned with what's right, what's wrong, as I walk these paths in these

00:42:29.600 --> 00:42:35.920
[Guest]: lands, I found the remnants, the strands of the intangible culture yet alive. That makes me say

00:42:35.920 --> 00:42:42.320
[Amit Varma]: that, okay, this was the society. Is this what you mean by what you said earlier about losing

00:42:42.320 --> 00:42:48.240
[Guest]: your faith and then regaining it? Yeah. I mean, you have to grow in a condition, environment,

00:42:48.240 --> 00:42:53.360
[Guest]: and then you have to drop the barriers and the conditioning. It's like breaking the shell,

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:58.320
[Guest]: right? The egg shell, right? And you have to then now start re-looking at things. I am still

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:05.360
[Guest]: a proud Sikh. I am still a proud Khalsa. But the only thing I'm saying is the definition of what I

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:12.480
[Guest]: understand of the faith of the Indus belt was so beautiful, so broad, and Nanak was the entire

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:18.640
[Guest]: fabric of it. That needs to be re-looked in the India's context where the communities have got

00:43:18.640 --> 00:43:24.640
[Guest]: disseminated. And people don't understand this. So I think for that, I consider myself fortunate

00:43:24.640 --> 00:43:29.360
[Guest]: and thank the divine that you gave me this ability to walk the lands and interact and stay with

00:43:29.360 --> 00:43:35.120
[Guest]: those people. I spend days and nights with them. And my heart pains when I look at how the culture

00:43:35.120 --> 00:43:40.160
[Guest]: is now in small pockets. You know, when communities get in a holocaust, when they move out, the ones

00:43:40.160 --> 00:43:46.480
[Guest]: who chose to stay, they become inwards. So they start protecting themselves more. But that's where

00:43:46.480 --> 00:43:52.000
[Guest]: lies the beauty. Because when you parachute inside that society seven decades later, you find that

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:57.040
[Guest]: they protected a strand that is lost elsewhere, that's gone elsewhere else. So here you still

00:43:57.040 --> 00:44:01.920
[Guest]: find it still protected because they become inwards now. They built a fort around themselves.

00:44:01.920 --> 00:44:05.600
[Guest]: They don't want to lose that. And you managed to get inside that, you parachuted from nowhere,

00:44:05.600 --> 00:44:11.360
[Guest]: and you suddenly see and say, ah, this is what my father used to talk about. This is what I used to

00:44:11.360 --> 00:44:15.920
[Guest]: hear about. This is what I've read about. And I'm finding the living strands of that. And it was a

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:23.440
[Guest]: very, very progressive society. And I want to deviate a little bit into the remnants of the art

00:44:23.440 --> 00:44:28.240
[Guest]: and try and understand the culture. So in The Ruins, in my second book, The Quest Continues,

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:31.760
[Guest]: I've shown a lot of pictures. I don't try and interpret a lot of stuff, you know, because I've

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:36.240
[Guest]: chosen not to do that. I want the viewer to interpret it themselves. I'm not trying to

00:44:36.240 --> 00:44:39.840
[Guest]: handhold you and take you through. I'm just describing my journey. But I've given you so

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:45.360
[Guest]: much of visual material in there that if you are having the open mind to look at them and not

00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:50.960
[Guest]: discard it because it goes beyond the domains of your conditioned mind, then you will find a lot of

00:44:50.960 --> 00:44:56.320
[Guest]: answers in it. But you will have to find the answers. In my calls, in my talks, in my discussions

00:44:56.320 --> 00:45:00.000
[Guest]: with people, I will, wherever there's an opportunity, give my thoughts, but I don't write

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:04.560
[Guest]: it everything. So I'll give you two things from art and talk about the culture itself.

00:45:05.280 --> 00:45:12.240
[Guest]: So I find in one of the places of worship, a fresco of a woman leading a hunt. It's in the

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:17.600
[Guest]: second book. And she's leading a hunt and catching hold of a blackbuck deer.

00:45:19.280 --> 00:45:25.760
[Guest]: And there's a man sitting on a horse behind, chilling it out with a hawk on his arm. So there

00:45:25.760 --> 00:45:30.320
[Guest]: are two things that I take from it. One is blackbuck. Blackbuck, that means was there in Punjab

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:34.160
[Guest]: too. That's why you're hunting in Punjab. Today you don't have it because the environment has

00:45:34.160 --> 00:45:39.760
[Guest]: changed in the 200, 300 years. The environment has changed from forests. A land of five rivers would

00:45:39.760 --> 00:45:44.000
[Guest]: not be an agricultural land. They'll be heavily forested, right? If you read the Umdat-Uttarik,

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:48.960
[Guest]: the day-to-day account of Ranjit Singh's period, they're going into forests. That forest is totally

00:45:48.960 --> 00:45:53.360
[Guest]: gone. It's an agricultural land. Punjab today is absolutely manicured, pedicured land, right?

00:45:53.360 --> 00:45:58.800
[Guest]: But there were black bucks moving around. Ranjit Singh's troops have hunted lions and tigers there.

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:04.560
[Guest]: So they were there. One of the wildlife thing. I'm coming to more of a deeper meaning out here.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:09.280
[Guest]: This fresco probably is 200 years old. 200, 250. I can't put a date to it. I'm just saying probably,

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:15.040
[Guest]: right? That means 250 years back, the society in the Indus belt was believing in women's

00:46:15.040 --> 00:46:20.080
[Guest]: empowerment because she was leading a hunt. Man was chilling behind. Women's empowerment

00:46:20.080 --> 00:46:26.320
[Guest]: in today's world is 250 years old. It's 250 years late, sorry. 250 years late. In Punjab,

00:46:26.320 --> 00:46:33.520
[Guest]: our forefathers were much ahead. Today, we have regressed. Today, Punjab cannot claim to be the

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:37.520
[Guest]: place where there's women's empowerment. We have regressed. But my forefathers were much more

00:46:37.520 --> 00:46:41.440
[Guest]: forward. That's what I take from that art. Otherwise, that art would not exist there.

00:46:41.440 --> 00:46:46.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one wonders if the art is an outlier. I mean, I did an episode with Madhvi Menon on the

00:46:46.240 --> 00:46:50.400
[Amit Varma]: history of desire in India. And it's certainly true that there were many different kinds of

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:55.360
[Amit Varma]: expression given to desire. And women could be, you know, could have lived different lives there.

00:46:55.360 --> 00:46:59.520
[Amit Varma]: But I am really not sure looking through history with the limited knowledge I have

00:46:59.520 --> 00:47:02.560
[Guest]: that women were ever empowered. I would always kind of been.

00:47:03.280 --> 00:47:09.680
[Guest]: And in the context of Punjab, I would not agree because empowerment starts from a philosophical

00:47:09.680 --> 00:47:12.800
[Guest]: seed first. If philosophically you don't believe in empowerment,

00:47:12.800 --> 00:47:18.400
[Guest]: an art as an expression cannot come out. So first, let's then step back. Nanak says in his writings,

00:47:21.280 --> 00:47:25.440
[Guest]: why do you call her inferior? Who gives birth to the greatest of the kings?

00:47:25.440 --> 00:47:29.600
[Guest]: Why do you call her inferior? Nanak is talking 500 years back about women's

00:47:30.960 --> 00:47:37.360
[Amit Varma]: equality in the society. On the one hand, this sounds fairly enlightened. But on the other hand,

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:41.840
[Amit Varma]: one could also argue that this takes a paternalistic view of a woman in the sense

00:47:41.840 --> 00:47:44.800
[Amit Varma]: saying that she is valuable because she gives birth to men.

00:47:44.800 --> 00:47:48.880
[Guest]: Yeah. But at the same place, he's writing in other places also about the glory of the woman,

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:51.440
[Amit Varma]: right? She's, I mean, But through the male gaze,

00:47:51.440 --> 00:47:53.600
[Amit Varma]: right? Through the male gaze, like in this example,

00:47:53.600 --> 00:47:59.120
[Guest]: I think there are many other verses which are talking about her status in the society. Of

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:03.440
[Guest]: course, there's a maternal aspect, there's a nurturing aspect of the female species. And

00:48:03.440 --> 00:48:07.440
[Guest]: today, I'm not trying to say women's empowerment today's context of that everyone needs to be in

00:48:07.440 --> 00:48:10.960
[Guest]: the workforce and this and that. I'm not passing any judgment on that. But they were being put on

00:48:10.960 --> 00:48:14.960
[Guest]: a pedestal with the natural instincts kept into them.

00:48:14.960 --> 00:48:20.080
[Amit Varma]: And certainly relative to the times. Absolutely. So I think there is the art,

00:48:20.080 --> 00:48:25.120
[Guest]: as I look at it, it had its some imprints into that. Of course, there's a lot of and I will not

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:29.760
[Guest]: the strategy is not perfect. But these are the glimpses that you get because there are

00:48:29.760 --> 00:48:33.760
[Guest]: cracks in the society, right? There are always cracks. The second one I want to talk about is

00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:37.920
[Guest]: very interesting fresco again, that you find frescoes inside some of these ruins of spiritual

00:48:37.920 --> 00:48:44.320
[Guest]: sites of a gurdwara that I saw Shravan Kumar holding his parents in the two tokris on the

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:50.080
[Guest]: two baskets and walking. Now I look at that and say, wow, so Shravan Kumar is not about any religion.

00:48:50.080 --> 00:48:56.080
[Guest]: It's not about any religion. It's about respect to your parents that transcends every religion.

00:48:56.080 --> 00:49:02.080
[Guest]: It's a basic fundamental duty, right? And Shravan Kumar finds a space inside the artwork of a

00:49:02.080 --> 00:49:08.720
[Guest]: gurdwara. And then I ask myself, will he find space in the artwork of a gurdwara today? Probably not

00:49:08.720 --> 00:49:13.200
[Guest]: because he's not wearing a turban. That makes you think that, okay, here's a strand which I see in

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:17.600
[Guest]: the past of what the culture was, what the society was and where we are today. I'm not passing

00:49:17.600 --> 00:49:22.160
[Guest]: judgment as to what has led to there, but it allows you to go back in time and then start

00:49:22.160 --> 00:49:25.920
[Guest]: asking certain questions. That's what I'm doing again and again. I'm not writing everything in

00:49:25.920 --> 00:49:30.880
[Guest]: my books, but I'm requesting the viewer to delve into the pictures and see for yourself.

00:49:30.880 --> 00:49:34.640
[Amit Varma]: In fact, some of the pictures I found really fascinating in your book is in your chapter on

00:49:34.640 --> 00:49:40.000
[Amit Varma]: the Baba Dhan Singh Gurdwara at Kot Fateh Khan, you've shown frescoes of Shiva, Nandi and Ganesh

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:44.240
[Amit Varma]: and then Brahma, Vishnu and Shiva. And, you know, again, that was something I kind of had to spot.

00:49:44.240 --> 00:49:48.160
[Amit Varma]: You don't have much commentary on that. You've just laid it out for, you know, people to see

00:49:48.160 --> 00:49:52.960
[Amit Varma]: and sort of think for themselves. In another chapter, you show Nanihal Singh's Haveli where,

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:57.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, there's a Rang Mahal on the roof and there you see Krishna listening to music and

00:49:57.200 --> 00:50:03.840
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. How did you train yourself to be able to look at these frescoes and sort of

00:50:03.840 --> 00:50:09.680
[Amit Varma]: identify who the characters are or even other nuances like elsewhere you have, you know,

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:15.040
[Amit Varma]: identified a building and said the bricks that were used here were of a time of Ranjit Singh's

00:50:15.040 --> 00:50:19.600
[Amit Varma]: time so we can date it accordingly. What was some of this knowledge part of the layers of

00:50:19.600 --> 00:50:24.960
[Amit Varma]: knowledge you were building up before you embarked on this quest or was it during this quest that you

00:50:24.960 --> 00:50:29.040
[Amit Varma]: kept refining your understanding? So, first and foremost thing, you're talking about Nanihal's

00:50:29.600 --> 00:50:33.760
[Guest]: Haveli and you talk about Krishna and you talk about other things. Yes, you find a variety of

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:38.000
[Guest]: art form but I just want to point out there's one picture in there. Don't miss it. Go and look

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:44.560
[Guest]: by the picture again. There's also a Masjid in that. I missed it. Yeah. So, it's not, all I'm

00:50:44.560 --> 00:50:50.160
[Guest]: trying to say it's not one view, right? So, in his bedroom, which is, I'm assuming it's his bedroom

00:50:50.160 --> 00:50:55.600
[Guest]: because it's his living place, he's got arts of the entire culture, the composite culture of Punjab.

00:50:56.240 --> 00:51:02.400
[Guest]: Even Masjid is there. So, let's not just see the present Hindu aspect of it. There are Sikh gurus

00:51:02.400 --> 00:51:07.360
[Guest]: there, there is Masjid there. So, they are reflecting the culture of Punjab in their bedroom,

00:51:07.360 --> 00:51:12.720
[Guest]: right? I think that's the key thing out here. As far as the identification of bricks and the other,

00:51:12.720 --> 00:51:16.640
[Guest]: many other things, I think it's not, your question is not about the bricks itself but the many layers

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:22.640
[Guest]: that we're talking about. It's a process. It doesn't happen overnight. As I said, don't follow

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:28.800
[Guest]: your passion. Create your passion. When you create your passion, every moment is a question. Every

00:51:28.800 --> 00:51:34.480
[Guest]: moment is a question. In my talk to you right now, I'm probing certain things inside my mind, right?

00:51:34.480 --> 00:51:40.880
[Guest]: Yeah. Every moment becomes a question when you start creating your passion and therefore every

00:51:40.880 --> 00:51:47.120
[Guest]: moment becomes a learning space. I am not born historian. I am not an historian. I'm an electronics

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:52.720
[Guest]: engineer who's done MBA, who's walked in the path of the finance industry. I was the revenue

00:51:52.720 --> 00:51:58.080
[Guest]: management head for Asia Pacific. I'm not trained for these things, but I've forced myself to start

00:51:58.080 --> 00:52:03.520
[Guest]: asking questions in those creating passion sub-segments of my life of four to five years

00:52:03.520 --> 00:52:08.080
[Guest]: that I was doing very passionately. And when you start doing that, you don't know what question

00:52:08.080 --> 00:52:13.680
[Guest]: will come to your mind. So I'm not trying to go into a classroom environment, but I'm curious enough

00:52:13.680 --> 00:52:18.400
[Guest]: to look at things and try and find answers. Okay, so why is this brick thinner than the bricks that

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:23.440
[Guest]: I see today? In the thin bricks, I find certain bricks are bigger in size and certain are smaller

00:52:23.440 --> 00:52:27.200
[Guest]: in size. They are thin. Now you're going to have to look at that. Why is this larger? Why is this

00:52:27.200 --> 00:52:31.040
[Guest]: thin? What period are they coming from? Because bricks are made in kilns, right? And people buy

00:52:31.040 --> 00:52:35.360
[Guest]: them and they make monuments. Monuments survive. Now you're going to look at the brick sizes to say

00:52:35.360 --> 00:52:40.880
[Guest]: which period it belongs to. There is a certain size of bricks in the Punjab region, which is

00:52:40.880 --> 00:52:47.440
[Guest]: known as Mughlai bricks, thin bricks, but broader. Then Ranjit Singh's period, the kilns, the casts

00:52:47.440 --> 00:52:52.880
[Guest]: for the bricks changed to smaller size, but still thin. So you look at the two, you can say this is

00:52:52.880 --> 00:52:57.840
[Unknown]: Mughlai period or Lodhi period, and this is the Ranjit Singh's period. And then you look at the

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:02.480
[Amit Varma]: British bricks, which become thick, what we use today. Much like the British themselves, as we now

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:12.000
[Guest]: know. So no comments on that, but yeah, so that's how you start, you know, probing. And the only

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:17.760
[Guest]: thing I can say is that knowledge is a process of layering. No one can claim to know anything

00:53:17.760 --> 00:53:23.040
[Guest]: and everything. I don't know anything and everything, but the layering will allow me to

00:53:23.040 --> 00:53:27.840
[Guest]: assimilate knowledge from the works done by the people in the past. And hopefully I'm adding my

00:53:27.840 --> 00:53:33.040
[Guest]: layer for the future generation to take away something from it. Knowledge comes in layers,

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:38.400
[Guest]: and knowledge will keep assimilating in layers. The question is, is the seeker showing it's his

00:53:38.400 --> 00:53:43.840
[Guest]: or her commitment to delve deeper into the layers of knowledge to understand what the person is

00:53:43.840 --> 00:53:48.880
[Amit Varma]: after? Very profound words. And I would add to that and say podcasts also come in layers. We

00:53:48.880 --> 00:53:53.680
[Amit Varma]: will now take a commercial break and come back after the break to add a layer of your personal

00:53:53.680 --> 00:54:00.800
[Amit Varma]: journeys to Pakistan. If you're listening to the scene in the unseen, it means you like listening

00:54:00.800 --> 00:54:05.680
[Amit Varma]: to audio and you're thirsty for knowledge. That being the case, I'd urge you to check out

