[Amit Varma]: Storytel, Where India Goes by Diane Coffey and Dean Spears. Download the Storytel app or visit

00:55:16.320 --> 00:55:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Storytel.com. Remember, that's Storytel with a single L. Storytel.com. Welcome back to The

00:55:22.960 --> 00:55:27.520
[Amit Varma]: Seen and The Unseen. I'm chatting with Amardeep Singh about his fascinating work looking at Sikh

00:55:27.520 --> 00:55:32.800
[Amit Varma]: legacy. Amardeep, let's kind of talk about your, you know, the first of your two projects, so to

00:55:32.800 --> 00:55:37.840
[Amit Varma]: say, which was traveling through Pakistan, which resulted in these two books and these two

00:55:37.840 --> 00:55:43.280
[Amit Varma]: documentaries. And you know, you start your book Lost Heritage by sort of injecting a personal

00:55:43.280 --> 00:55:48.240
[Amit Varma]: note into it, where your father Sundar Singh in Gorakhpur receives a, you know, a postcard from

00:55:48.240 --> 00:55:53.200
[Amit Varma]: Rawalpindi. Tell me a little bit about that. And was your sort of family history where there's a

00:55:53.200 --> 00:55:59.520
[Amit Varma]: lot more history, which goes back to the trauma of partition? Was that part of what drove you on

00:55:59.520 --> 00:56:06.400
[Guest]: your quest? Yes, it's there's a personal aspect to this whole quest, which has transformed from

00:56:06.400 --> 00:56:12.560
[Guest]: a very personal probing to documenting for the broader communities. So it's a transformation

00:56:12.560 --> 00:56:19.360
[Guest]: of a personal quest. I didn't go into Pakistan, to be honest, to write any book. It just happened.

00:56:19.360 --> 00:56:22.960
[Guest]: Because when I left the corporate world, I just thought I'm actually in between something. And

00:56:22.960 --> 00:56:26.560
[Guest]: the doors were shut for a little while. And I think Divine was trying to push me in this direction.

00:56:26.560 --> 00:56:30.560
[Guest]: And when I decided to walk in, the gates started opening. So Divine was waiting for me to take

00:56:30.560 --> 00:56:34.720
[Guest]: the step and then started opening the gates. But in that opening of the gates, I stepped in

00:56:34.720 --> 00:56:40.320
[Guest]: with a simple quest as to my father was not able to go back to Muzaffarabad in Pakistan's Kashmir.

00:56:40.320 --> 00:56:44.640
[Guest]: And my mother was from Abbottabad. Both of them could not go. So I wanted to and there are no

00:56:44.640 --> 00:56:52.240
[Guest]: more. So I wanted to see if I can go in and see the places. And then the layers of my own building

00:56:52.240 --> 00:56:57.840
[Guest]: on creating of passions that I was doing had prepared me over the time as a photographer,

00:56:57.840 --> 00:57:05.680
[Guest]: as a small visual narrative writer, as having enough knowledge about history, about spirituality,

00:57:05.680 --> 00:57:10.880
[Guest]: about not just my faith, many other faiths, all the layers were prepared. And when I stepped inside,

00:57:10.880 --> 00:57:16.160
[Guest]: the gates started opening up for me. But I only went in with a personal quest. But what I saw

00:57:16.160 --> 00:57:21.200
[Guest]: and I felt that I came back with 36 cities and villages in a span of 30 days, I said, wow, this

00:57:21.200 --> 00:57:27.760
[Guest]: is a huge land that I've traversed in just 30 days. And should I just sit back or should I write

00:57:27.760 --> 00:57:33.520
[Guest]: this for posterity? Because like me, which was a personal quest, you said your father was from

00:57:33.520 --> 00:57:39.280
[Guest]: Sheikhupura. I'm sure you have a desire too. I'm sure there are many others who have a desire.

00:57:39.280 --> 00:57:43.920
[Guest]: I'm sure there are many Muslims on the other side who have a desire to come to UP and Bihar.

00:57:43.920 --> 00:57:50.320
[Guest]: It's a human aspect. It's a human need to kind of connect to your roots. And the hardened boundaries

00:57:50.320 --> 00:57:55.840
[Guest]: don't allow us to do that today. So if a divine energy has blessed you, should you keep it back

00:57:55.840 --> 00:58:02.800
[Guest]: to your own quest? Or should you open it up? I may not be able to take you into your personal journey,

00:58:02.800 --> 00:58:08.080
[Guest]: but I can give you a glimpse of the journey that makes you curious enough and you don't know how

00:58:08.080 --> 00:58:14.240
[Guest]: these things will develop. And I've often said in my talks is I am waiting for a day when a Hindu

00:58:14.240 --> 00:58:19.120
[Guest]: will get up and say, I will document the Hindu legacy in Pakistan. A Jain will get up and say,

00:58:19.120 --> 00:58:23.680
[Guest]: I will document Jain legacy in Pakistan. And I'm waiting for a day when a Muslim will get up in

00:58:23.680 --> 00:58:28.880
[Guest]: Pakistan and say, I will document the Islamic legacy in East Punjab. The day we've done that,

00:58:28.880 --> 00:58:34.000
[Guest]: in 10 volumes, we will have the Punjabi legacy. Until that time, I'm only one piece of the

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:40.320
[Guest]: equation. So you are planting seeds for the wider communities to now start exploring their roots.

00:58:40.880 --> 00:58:45.120
[Guest]: And this is a natural formal path of putting layers of information where these things will

00:58:45.120 --> 00:58:49.840
[Guest]: grow. And I thank myself that in the five years that I've seen, and I'm not the only

00:58:49.840 --> 00:58:55.040
[Guest]: person who can take credit there. Many forces have come together, but I look at the picture

00:58:55.040 --> 00:58:59.760
[Guest]: of the first book, the front cover picture of the broken Dera Chauha Baba Guru Nanak Gurdwara,

00:58:59.760 --> 00:59:05.280
[Guest]: the historical Gurdwara. Between 2014, when I went there, and when we are sitting here last year,

00:59:05.280 --> 00:59:09.840
[Guest]: it was announced that Gurdwara will be maintained like that. Many others have been decided to be

00:59:09.840 --> 00:59:14.560
[Guest]: maintained. I don't take the credit for it, but I know in the quarters that I've dealt with,

00:59:14.560 --> 00:59:20.240
[Guest]: the initial reaction was, why have you not shown Nankana Sahib in the front cover? But I said,

00:59:20.240 --> 00:59:24.000
[Guest]: I have shown it inside. I've shown the things that are working well. I've shown where the

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:27.680
[Guest]: opportunities lie. And to me, these are opportunities. And my feeling is, it's my

00:59:27.680 --> 00:59:33.440
[Guest]: heritage which is lost because another Amardeep may not be permitted. Another XYZ may not be

00:59:33.440 --> 00:59:38.720
[Guest]: permitted. And therefore, it's lost from us. And I want us to think that there's a potential inside

00:59:38.720 --> 00:59:43.120
[Guest]: this. And that potential is what can then transform and bring about change, right?

00:59:43.120 --> 00:59:47.280
[Guest]: So I think the answer to your question is that we have to do the right thing. We can't control

00:59:47.280 --> 00:59:51.840
[Guest]: every outcome. But if we do the right thing, I think it leads us to the right direction in terms

00:59:51.840 --> 00:59:56.320
[Amit Varma]: of bringing about change. And it kind of seems to me that when you travel through Pakistan,

00:59:56.320 --> 01:00:01.120
[Amit Varma]: you went simultaneously on three different kinds of journeys. One is an intellectual journey of

01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:06.160
[Amit Varma]: trying to understand what happened and all the dissipations and to figure out what remains.

01:00:06.160 --> 01:00:12.240
[Amit Varma]: One is sort of, in a sense, a spiritual journey of understanding Nanak's legacy and Nanak's message,

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:17.840
[Amit Varma]: so to say. And I'll ask you about both of those later. But you also went on an emotional journey

01:00:17.840 --> 01:00:22.560
[Amit Varma]: where you're revisiting what is part of your past. For example, Muzaffarabad, you know, you point out

01:00:22.560 --> 01:00:27.920
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, the postcard that your father in Gorakhpur received was from a long lost nephew

01:00:27.920 --> 01:00:32.800
[Amit Varma]: who had been separated from your aunt in Muzaffarabad when, you know, the two kids, 10 and

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:37.200
[Amit Varma]: 8, were separated from their mother. And then they landed up on the other side. You also talk about

01:00:37.200 --> 01:00:42.960
[Amit Varma]: your aunt, Inder Kaur, throwing her infant girl off the bridge in Muzaffarabad. And she died,

01:00:42.960 --> 01:00:48.160
[Amit Varma]: of course. And you actually went to that bridge. You actually saw the place where all these corpses

01:00:48.160 --> 01:00:54.320
[Amit Varma]: of your community and some of your family had actually lain there. What are sort of your

01:00:54.320 --> 01:00:58.960
[Amit Varma]: feelings when you're visiting not just foreign towns, but also parts of your own past?

01:00:59.600 --> 01:01:03.200
[Guest]: It's an interesting question you ask, right? Basically, you're asking what's my emotional

01:01:03.200 --> 01:01:05.200
[Guest]: state, right? In other words,

01:01:05.920 --> 01:01:10.880
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, and does it evolve? Like, are you then able to like, these quests are happening

01:01:10.880 --> 01:01:14.400
[Amit Varma]: simultaneously. At one level, there is an intellectual understanding, like you write

01:01:14.400 --> 01:01:18.960
[Amit Varma]: about how you have decided at an intellectual level that you're not going to pass judgment

01:01:18.960 --> 01:01:22.480
[Amit Varma]: on characters in history. You're just going to document what happened and what there is.

01:01:22.480 --> 01:01:27.840
[Guest]: But at another level, you are deeply affected. So I think let's start with the second piece.

01:01:27.840 --> 01:01:32.400
[Guest]: Am I deeply affected? It's a question I ask myself, right? I'm going to give you an answer,

01:01:32.400 --> 01:01:37.120
[Guest]: which is going to be absolutely 180 degrees on the other end of the spectrum of what you're

01:01:37.120 --> 01:01:42.000
[Guest]: thinking or what everyone thinks. The reality is when you go on this quest, I never went to

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:45.760
[Guest]: write the first book. You've got to understand that. I never went to write the second book.

01:01:45.760 --> 01:01:50.640
[Guest]: I never went to make the two documentaries. The only time I've consciously went, the two

01:01:50.640 --> 01:01:54.560
[Guest]: documentaries on Sikh legacy in Pakistan, the only time I've consciously went in search of

01:01:54.560 --> 01:01:59.840
[Guest]: something knowingly that it may not be possible because the task was too huge is the making of

01:01:59.840 --> 01:02:03.200
[Guest]: Allegory and Tapestry of Guru Nanak's Travels, right? That's the only thing that has happened

01:02:03.200 --> 01:02:07.280
[Guest]: in the last one year. But before that, for four years, I've done everything unknowingly.

01:02:07.280 --> 01:02:12.240
[Guest]: So I've gone inside because the energy opens up. I go inside and I start probing. I have the history

01:02:12.240 --> 01:02:17.360
[Guest]: in mind. I have the other stuff in mind. But when I go to the place, the curious mind of mine does

01:02:17.360 --> 01:02:23.440
[Guest]: not have the bandwidth for any emotions because I'm wearing 10 antennas on my head at that point

01:02:23.440 --> 01:02:30.320
[Guest]: of time. I'm wearing the antenna of that emotional handshake and the coming together of people and

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:34.880
[Guest]: the welcoming aspect, you know, that's the human aspect. People welcome you and other things,

01:02:34.880 --> 01:02:38.720
[Guest]: right? That's one thing you have to manage. Secondly, you're going to manage the, there are

01:02:38.720 --> 01:02:42.320
[Guest]: questions and there are doubts as to this man has come inside. Why has he come so deep inside? There

01:02:42.320 --> 01:02:46.480
[Guest]: are agencies that will be questioning you and there'll be other people questioning the people

01:02:46.480 --> 01:02:49.920
[Guest]: who have doubts on you. Why have you come here? You've got to manage that aspect because that can

01:02:49.920 --> 01:02:55.200
[Guest]: become a barrier in your quest, right? You've got to manage your time because there's a cost

01:02:55.200 --> 01:02:59.120
[Guest]: associated with that time, right? And you've got to move fast. And you are doing 36 cities and

01:02:59.120 --> 01:03:03.280
[Guest]: villages in 30 days. You've got to move fast. You go into a monument, there's a whole village that

01:03:03.280 --> 01:03:07.440
[Guest]: gathers there. In that village, you don't want to be there for long because they are seeing a Sikh

01:03:07.440 --> 01:03:11.280
[Guest]: for the first time after seven decades, right? I'm visible a Sikh, right? So you've got to get in and

01:03:11.280 --> 01:03:15.600
[Guest]: get out fast. And then you've got to look at the frescoes, the ruins, the remnants, absorb all

01:03:15.600 --> 01:03:20.000
[Guest]: that aspect. There's a lot happening in a short span of time. In that whole scheme of thing,

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:23.840
[Guest]: in the moment, there's no scope for emotion. You can't sit and ponder by the bank.

01:03:23.840 --> 01:03:27.680
[Guest]: No, there's no time. This is where people think that you're on a holiday. No, you're on a holiday.

01:03:27.680 --> 01:03:30.960
[Guest]: 36 cities and villages in 30 days. You're going from one end of the country to the other end of

01:03:30.960 --> 01:03:34.000
[Guest]: the country. You're getting up at 3 a.m. and you're on the road, coming back at 11 o'clock,

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:39.440
[Guest]: backing up the data. It's a huge, humongous task. There is no scope for emotion. And I'm glad there's

01:03:39.440 --> 01:03:43.200
[Guest]: no scope for emotion because the day there's emotion in the fieldwork, your fieldwork is

01:03:43.200 --> 01:03:48.160
[Guest]: biased. Fieldwork has to be always emotionless. Then you start looking at the layers when you

01:03:48.160 --> 01:03:52.800
[Guest]: come back. Does the emotion come later? Yes. When you come back and you start looking at,

01:03:52.800 --> 01:03:55.280
[Guest]: and you lie down on your bed and you start looking at the ceiling above and say,

01:03:55.280 --> 01:03:59.120
[Guest]: what happened just now? Something happened, right? And you say, my God, this was like a

01:03:59.120 --> 01:04:03.760
[Guest]: journey of a lifetime, right? And then you say, oh, I saw this aspect. And you start interpreting

01:04:03.760 --> 01:04:06.960
[Guest]: it. And then you start writing down. I never went to write a book. Then you start writing down.

01:04:06.960 --> 01:04:11.120
[Guest]: That's where the emotion starts coming. But it's a very task-oriented writing because you're trying

01:04:11.120 --> 01:04:14.640
[Guest]: to do the whole thing. What takes five to six years in a PhD environment, you're doing in just

01:04:14.640 --> 01:04:19.680
[Guest]: seven to eight months. You're doing very fast. You're just purging all the information down

01:04:19.680 --> 01:04:24.720
[Guest]: from your mind into the paper, right? The emotion starts coming out really in this whole process is

01:04:24.720 --> 01:04:28.960
[Guest]: when you start presenting to the audience and you see the audience is now connecting. And that's

01:04:28.960 --> 01:04:34.080
[Guest]: where your inner state is saying, I'm glad we did this. That's where the emotion starts coming out.

01:04:34.080 --> 01:04:38.880
[Guest]: When the audience emotes, then you also have an emotional aspect coming out, right? So that's

01:04:38.880 --> 01:04:44.240
[Guest]: the reality of the whole thing. And I'm glad it is the way it is because fieldwork should never

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:48.800
[Guest]: be influenced by emotion. And when you do that, then you have the ability of seeing different

01:04:48.800 --> 01:04:55.760
[Guest]: strands coming out. A lot of people say to me that these works are going beyond the Sikh domain.

01:04:55.760 --> 01:05:00.080
[Guest]: And I say, you know what? You've not understood it. You've not understood the culture of the past.

01:05:00.080 --> 01:05:03.520
[Guest]: And these strands are the only strands that you have. You can't throw the baby in the bathtub

01:05:03.520 --> 01:05:08.160
[Guest]: out. You've got to keep the strand the way it is. Right or wrong, let's not pass judgments

01:05:08.160 --> 01:05:11.600
[Guest]: because my forefathers have made it. Our forefathers were collectively living, they have

01:05:11.600 --> 01:05:16.400
[Amit Varma]: made it. Let's try and understand from it and figure out what is it. I'm going to play a brief

01:05:16.400 --> 01:05:20.640
[Amit Varma]: clip. And of course, I'll play the audio, but I saw it on video in the second of your documentaries.

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:26.880
[Amit Varma]: And that kind of moved me a bit where a gentleman named Aslam at Toha Khalsa talks about a massacre

01:05:26.880 --> 01:05:32.880
[Amit Varma]: that happened there just before partition, where a massacre of Sikhs, where a lot of women gave

01:05:32.880 --> 01:05:37.600
[Amit Varma]: their lives by jumping into a well. And you were actually at that well. And this gentleman was at

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:42.560
[Amit Varma]: that well with you. And he told you what he saw. And when I saw it, of course, I found it very

01:05:42.560 --> 01:05:46.400
[Amit Varma]: affecting. So I'm going to briefly play that audio clip and then translate.

01:06:13.520 --> 01:06:18.480
[Amit Varma]: Right. So here's the translation of what Aslam says. He's asked where he was standing. And he

01:06:18.480 --> 01:06:24.000
[Amit Varma]: says, quote, right at that spot. Many women were standing outside while some had jumped in the well.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:28.960
[Amit Varma]: There was no space left in the well as it was filled with bodies till the top. The ones yet

01:06:28.960 --> 01:06:34.960
[Amit Varma]: alive in the well were trying to immerse their head in the water. They wanted to die. Stop quote.

01:06:34.960 --> 01:06:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And all this again, you know, when you read about it, when you go there, you've written also about

01:06:38.480 --> 01:06:42.720
[Amit Varma]: the rape of Rawalpindi, for example, all the violence that happened. And again, for all of

01:06:42.720 --> 01:06:46.400
[Amit Varma]: this, you're saying that you process it later. When you are there, you're just in the moment,

01:06:46.400 --> 01:06:51.520
[Guest]: you have to get the data and you have to get out. Absolutely. Because it's a very complex

01:06:51.520 --> 01:06:55.680
[Guest]: thing in the limited time frame that you're there to access data. If you can get the data,

01:06:55.680 --> 01:07:00.240
[Guest]: then you understand after that. But you see, this work cannot be done if the divine is not

01:07:00.240 --> 01:07:06.000
[Guest]: going to help you in this whole process. You only have the desire. Now, the desire gets me into

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:11.280
[Guest]: Tuha Khalsa village, which itself is in a restricted area. You can't get inside Tuha Khalsa very easily.

01:07:11.280 --> 01:07:18.000
[Guest]: I've reached the village. How do I find that well? This generation that saw it is nearing its end,

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:23.200
[Guest]: right? There may not be anyone alive. So how do you stumble upon some man who then takes you to

01:07:23.200 --> 01:07:29.680
[Guest]: his home and his mother, who's 92 years old, Muzammil Bibi, meets you and she says how great

01:07:29.680 --> 01:07:36.480
[Guest]: Tuha was before 47. It was a big town and she talks about a Hindu and seek her friends. And

01:07:36.480 --> 01:07:42.880
[Guest]: she's remembering the girls with whom she used to play. But she was probably at that time,

01:07:42.880 --> 01:07:47.040
[Guest]: 92 years, 22 years old. She's 92 years now. So she was 22 years old at that time.

01:07:48.240 --> 01:07:53.040
[Guest]: And then from there, as you're walking out, you're trying to find the well. She's too old. She says,

01:07:53.040 --> 01:08:00.400
[Guest]: oh well, it happened. That well is there. But how do you go there? Where is it? People don't

01:08:00.400 --> 01:08:04.720
[Guest]: understand it. The new generation has not bothered about it. And you come out and you suddenly see

01:08:04.720 --> 01:08:09.440
[Guest]: an old man walking with his stick on the road. And I stopped the vehicle and I went to him and

01:08:09.440 --> 01:08:15.200
[Guest]: I said, Baba Salaam. And he looks at me from his broken glasses, you know, he looks at me and he

01:08:15.200 --> 01:08:20.960
[Guest]: says, how did you come here? Because he's seeing a visible Sikh, right? And I tell him and then I

01:08:20.960 --> 01:08:30.480
[Guest]: asked him, do you know, do you know the well where the women jumped in 47? He says, I was present

01:08:30.480 --> 01:08:37.120
[Guest]: there. How do you describe that? You will bump into someone who is an eyewitness random in a

01:08:37.120 --> 01:08:42.160
[Guest]: short span of just a short visit to that village. And that person then takes you there. These are

01:08:42.160 --> 01:08:49.840
[Guest]: divine blessings. So your understanding of the narrative is being propelled by a divine push.

01:08:49.840 --> 01:08:56.000
[Guest]: And then when you're there, when I saw the well, I didn't have a tear coming down of my eyes.

01:08:56.720 --> 01:09:01.360
[Guest]: It's contrary to what people would believe. I did not. Because for me, that moment is what I was

01:09:01.360 --> 01:09:05.920
[Guest]: trying to capture. What is it? And I know I will be able to lie down on the bed later on and reflect

01:09:05.920 --> 01:09:10.480
[Guest]: about it. In the moment, there was no emotion. But these emotions are being propelled by a force

01:09:10.480 --> 01:09:15.120
[Guest]: that's guiding you towards something. And that to me is a divine intervention. And I think the

01:09:15.120 --> 01:09:21.200
[Guest]: universe is waiting for, as I say, again, what we started off with, creating your passions. I think

01:09:21.200 --> 01:09:27.760
[Guest]: the universe is waiting for the commitment from you, the commitment from you over a period of 30

01:09:27.760 --> 01:09:32.880
[Guest]: years to say, now you're ready. Now I'm going to open the gates for you. And now wherever you will

01:09:32.880 --> 01:09:38.960
[Guest]: walk, whatever be your desire, it will be manifesting in front of you. And that's where

01:09:39.600 --> 01:09:44.080
[Amit Varma]: it all starts happening. So you mentioned that when you decided to go to Pakistan,

01:09:44.080 --> 01:09:48.320
[Amit Varma]: and I think you went in October 2014, you landed up the first time, the first time,

01:09:48.320 --> 01:09:52.480
[Amit Varma]: and you didn't intend to write a book, you didn't intend to make documentaries,

01:09:52.480 --> 01:09:57.120
[Guest]: what pushed you? Why were you going there? So I was, as I said, in the interim of my in the

01:09:57.120 --> 01:10:01.280
[Guest]: midway of moving out, I moved out from Amex, and I was supposed to go to Australia, I decided not to

01:10:01.280 --> 01:10:05.840
[Guest]: go, I was going to look for another job. And finding a job when you exit at a senior level

01:10:05.840 --> 01:10:10.880
[Guest]: takes a bit of time. And six months had passed by, I was going through the process. And I decided,

01:10:10.880 --> 01:10:16.400
[Guest]: now's the time, I should go to Pakistan. And I landed there. How I got my visa is a different

01:10:16.400 --> 01:10:21.040
[Guest]: story. I mean, how do I'm an Indian born, but I hold a Singaporean passport. In those days,

01:10:21.040 --> 01:10:24.320
[Guest]: still the question was, you're an Indian born, both the countries do the same thing to the people.

01:10:24.320 --> 01:10:28.240
[Guest]: If you are, so I have a friend who's Pakistani born, and he had a wedding to come to in Delhi,

01:10:28.240 --> 01:10:32.320
[Guest]: the wedding got over. And from four months after that, the visa got approved, right? So this is

01:10:32.320 --> 01:10:37.840
[Guest]: a problem for both the nations, right? So I apply for it, and I get it. And the next time I land in

01:10:37.840 --> 01:10:43.760
[Guest]: there, and then why did I meet that first person who held my hand? Six months prior to my going

01:10:43.760 --> 01:10:49.920
[Guest]: there, I had seen someone doing something similar, which was of my passion, some Pakistani. And I

01:10:49.920 --> 01:10:54.240
[Guest]: saw him and I asked him, why don't you click better pictures? He says, I don't have a camera.

01:10:54.240 --> 01:10:57.680
[Guest]: I just packed my camera and sent it to him, because I'm a photographer, I had many camera

01:10:57.680 --> 01:11:02.400
[Guest]: bodies. I just packed two lenses and one camera and sent it to him. The point is, why did it

01:11:02.400 --> 01:11:06.000
[Guest]: happen six months before? Because that person was already ready with that. Because I had done

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:11.040
[Guest]: something for me, for him, without him asking. And when I landed there, he was there to hold my hand.

01:11:11.040 --> 01:11:14.240
[Guest]: And one thing led to the other, to the other, to the other, and you did the whole journey.

01:11:15.200 --> 01:11:19.600
[Guest]: So you didn't go to write a book. But when you came back, that's when you started thinking,

01:11:19.600 --> 01:11:24.800
[Guest]: I went on a personal quest. I have seen Muzaffarabad. I had only two reasons. One is I

01:11:24.800 --> 01:11:31.040
[Guest]: want to see strands of my history. Are they still there? In the remnants, tangible and intangibles?

01:11:31.040 --> 01:11:32.240
[Guest]: Were they still there?

01:11:32.240 --> 01:11:34.480
[Guest]: Those are the monuments through which the lost heritage, the Sikh legacy.

01:11:34.480 --> 01:11:37.920
[Amit Varma]: That's a Sikh history. What strands of your history there? Did you feel that personal

01:11:37.920 --> 01:11:38.320
[Guest]: connection?

01:11:38.320 --> 01:11:42.400
[Guest]: So my history is my community's history, my Punjabi history, the Islamic history,

01:11:42.400 --> 01:11:44.480
[Unknown]: the Hindu history, the Jain history, the...

01:11:44.480 --> 01:11:45.840
[Guest]: The Nanak Panti history.

01:11:45.840 --> 01:11:50.560
[Guest]: Everything is my history. The lands are my history. I'm choosing to see it from a Sikh

01:11:50.560 --> 01:11:55.440
[Guest]: lens. But in that Sikh lens, you will find a lot of plurality actually intertwines, right?

01:11:56.720 --> 01:12:01.440
[Guest]: When you're talking earlier about the artwork inside Nonyal's Haveli and a Masjid and Krishna

01:12:01.440 --> 01:12:06.720
[Guest]: both exist there. It's our collective legacy, right? So I went to see that. And then when I

01:12:07.280 --> 01:12:11.760
[Guest]: was able to go into Multan and see the Anglo-Sikh, second Anglo-Sikh war monument there

01:12:11.760 --> 01:12:17.040
[Guest]: and find out that the Idgah where the second Anglo-Sikh war started because of Van Zagnew

01:12:17.040 --> 01:12:21.760
[Guest]: was beheaded there. It's not there. But the place around which where the Idgah was there,

01:12:21.760 --> 01:12:22.640
[Guest]: you see it, right?

01:12:22.640 --> 01:12:26.400
[Guest]: So you find these remnants and you start stitching the story together. When you come back,

01:12:26.400 --> 01:12:32.000
[Guest]: you feel propelled and compelled that it must be written because it's no more your quest. It

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:36.560
[Guest]: becomes a responsibility for the bigger communities and the wider communities and the inspiration

01:12:36.560 --> 01:12:41.120
[Guest]: that you can provide to them. That's how the first book happened. And I did it fast. I just did it

01:12:41.120 --> 01:12:45.440
[Guest]: because I was in a rush to get back into the corporate world. I never knew that this would

01:12:45.440 --> 01:12:50.000
[Guest]: become my life. I did it. And I didn't know that after I got it published, I faced a lot of

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:53.520
[Guest]: problems in publishing in the first book because I'm an unknown author. I'm coming from finance

01:12:53.520 --> 01:12:57.360
[Guest]: industry, trying to do a huge volume book. Publishers are there to make money out of it.

01:12:57.360 --> 01:13:01.120
[Guest]: They're looking at the commercial aspect, faced a lot of problems, but we managed to get it done.

01:13:01.120 --> 01:13:04.880
[Guest]: A lot of people came forward and saw my work and they helped me and thanked all of them.

01:13:04.880 --> 01:13:09.600
[Guest]: Once we got it published, I didn't realize that the world was waiting to hear the story.

01:13:10.320 --> 01:13:15.520
[Guest]: And then it just kept me on the road for a good 10 months. And I spoke at some 70-odd seminars

01:13:15.520 --> 01:13:19.760
[Guest]: around the world. And it didn't allow me to come back to Singapore for a good eight months. People

01:13:19.760 --> 01:13:24.080
[Guest]: kept moving me from one place to the other. So, eight months I was on the road. It's when I came

01:13:24.080 --> 01:13:29.200
[Guest]: back and then I started applying for the job, not two and a half years had passed by. And I was dead

01:13:29.200 --> 01:13:33.680
[Unknown]: meat for corporate industry. Because two and a half years is too late now, right? You've been far

01:13:33.680 --> 01:13:38.400
[Guest]: out and living in a senior role. And that's when I started reinventing myself. I said,

01:13:38.400 --> 01:13:43.200
[Guest]: no, I've got to restart this whole thing. So, I picked up a job in a startup. Something that I

01:13:43.200 --> 01:13:48.000
[Guest]: was doing at an intellectual level, what I was probably doing 20 years back in my career. My

01:13:48.000 --> 01:13:53.120
[Guest]: mind was not into it. And then the divine opened this gate again, because I used to dream of Jamrod.

01:13:53.840 --> 01:13:56.880
[Guest]: I used to dream of Jamrod at the Khyber Pass. I was looking at the Khyber Pass. I was standing

01:13:56.880 --> 01:14:00.560
[Amit Varma]: at Jamrod. I was advised not to go to Jamrod in my first book. And Jamrod, of course, for the

01:14:00.560 --> 01:14:05.440
[Amit Varma]: listeners, is a great fort at the Khyber Pass where Hari Singh Nalwa actually died, in fact.

01:14:05.440 --> 01:14:11.760
[Guest]: Yes. And it's the fort that finally plugged. It was a fort. It was made in just a few days

01:14:11.760 --> 01:14:16.720
[Guest]: and finally plugged the invasions from the Central Asia into the subcontinent.

01:14:16.720 --> 01:14:20.240
[Guest]: Because thereafter, the British came after the Sikh Empire. They came from the East. They didn't

01:14:20.240 --> 01:14:24.080
[Guest]: come from the West. No one has actually come from the West afterwards. So, that's a defining point

01:14:24.080 --> 01:14:27.760
[Guest]: of the history. And I was standing there. I couldn't go inside because I was advised not to

01:14:27.760 --> 01:14:34.160
[Guest]: go inside Jamrod. I was at Peshawar in the night before. This is 2014. The army school attack on

01:14:34.160 --> 01:14:38.240
[Guest]: the children happened at that time. Taliban, this thing was in the peak. There are some Sikh

01:14:39.200 --> 01:14:43.600
[Guest]: shopkeepers from Peshawar who have shops close to Jamrod. And I would ask them, can you take me in

01:14:43.600 --> 01:14:47.280
[Guest]: the morning? No one was wanting to take me. They didn't want to take risk. Because I look different,

01:14:47.280 --> 01:14:51.280
[Guest]: I talk different, I hold a camera body, and I could be a sitting duck, right? I could be easily

01:14:51.280 --> 01:14:54.800
[Guest]: abducted, right? No one wanted to take me. And I got up in the morning. I just got into a car,

01:14:54.800 --> 01:14:58.640
[Guest]: went there. But I couldn't go inside because that fort is with the army. And I clicked a picture

01:14:58.640 --> 01:15:03.440
[Guest]: from the outside and I came back. But between the first book and when the energy of the second book

01:15:03.440 --> 01:15:08.400
[Guest]: developed, as I was giving the talks around the world, I used to get dreams of Jamrod. I used to

01:15:08.400 --> 01:15:12.960
[Guest]: feel that I was so near and yet so far. I just stood across the road and I clicked a picture. I

01:15:12.960 --> 01:15:17.280
[Guest]: couldn't go inside. And you know when you feel something very strongly and passionately, the

01:15:17.280 --> 01:15:23.360
[Guest]: universe again answers. And I was in this job. I was doing it for three months. My mind was not

01:15:23.360 --> 01:15:28.640
[Guest]: into it. And one day I get a call from the embassy of Pakistan in Singapore. And Mr. Nasrullah Khan

01:15:28.640 --> 01:15:33.520
[Guest]: calls me. He says, come and meet us. I went there. He says, you know what? You did this first book.

01:15:33.520 --> 01:15:36.880
[Guest]: You went around the world. You called us to inaugurate the book in Singapore. I did call

01:15:36.880 --> 01:15:40.560
[Guest]: them, right? I must say that you've taken a very tricky subject and you've taken it around the

01:15:40.560 --> 01:15:44.560
[Guest]: world and you're not politicizing it. I said, there's nothing to politicize in it. I can't

01:15:44.560 --> 01:15:49.040
[Guest]: change the history. But what can I learn from it? And what can we all learn from it? And what can we

01:15:49.040 --> 01:15:52.720
[Guest]: motivate each other is the objective out here. And if you can actually openly talk about it,

01:15:52.720 --> 01:15:56.800
[Guest]: then we will all be in a better space. He says, no, I do hear you because you went around the

01:15:56.800 --> 01:16:01.040
[Guest]: world and we have got reports from all over that you've gone. Because I'm a Singaporean,

01:16:01.040 --> 01:16:04.640
[Guest]: so of course the reports would come on it because I'm talking about a subject of Pakistan.

01:16:04.640 --> 01:16:10.080
[Guest]: And so I'm quite impressed that you've had no political tension anywhere in your talks, right?

01:16:10.080 --> 01:16:15.440
[Guest]: So he says, we have selected you from our embassy on a academy of letters. It's like

01:16:15.440 --> 01:16:19.760
[Guest]: a Sahitya Kala Academy Awards. They have an academy of collectors. They want to bring in

01:16:19.760 --> 01:16:25.120
[Guest]: some foreign nationals to expose the artists in Islamabad to some foreign talent. So they said,

01:16:25.120 --> 01:16:28.880
[Guest]: from Singapore, we selected you. Would you be able to go there? I said, absolutely.

01:16:29.600 --> 01:16:33.840
[Guest]: So I went in, I took that invitation. I took a leave from my job for five days.

01:16:33.840 --> 01:16:41.200
[Guest]: And Jan, 2016, I was in Pakistan. No, Jan, 2017, I was in Pakistan for five days. And then the

01:16:41.200 --> 01:16:46.000
[Guest]: energy that developed again when I was there, I should still get the gleam of Jamrod. And I met

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:50.480
[Guest]: some people who had heard me and they were in influential quarters. And then I requested to

01:16:50.480 --> 01:16:56.720
[Guest]: them that I'm here. Please open the Jamrod Fort for me. Next, I know the fort opened. Next,

01:16:56.720 --> 01:17:01.200
[Guest]: I asked for Attaq. Next, I asked for Shabkadar. Everything started opening. I couldn't describe

01:17:01.200 --> 01:17:06.640
[Guest]: this. I could feel that the energy is now in my favor again. And I asked myself this question,

01:17:06.640 --> 01:17:11.040
[Guest]: do I walk away right now for that job, which I don't enjoy? I just picked up the phone and

01:17:11.040 --> 01:17:15.520
[Guest]: called them that I'm resigning. I was there for five days. I came out of the country after 55

01:17:15.520 --> 01:17:20.400
[Guest]: days. And in that process, I went after the force that I was shown to me. I just went on my own,

01:17:20.400 --> 01:17:26.240
[Guest]: just went deeper and deeper. 90 cities and villages. I came back and I just couldn't hold

01:17:26.240 --> 01:17:30.000
[Guest]: myself back. I said, this is, again, something that needs to be shared with the world because

01:17:30.000 --> 01:17:35.760
[Guest]: now I've documented a huge amount of data about the culture, the intangible aspects in Balochistan,

01:17:35.760 --> 01:17:41.120
[Guest]: living communities, the hidden treasures inside this of the Sikh era forts and other things.

01:17:41.120 --> 01:17:45.360
[Guest]: I just couldn't sit back. I just started writing immediately. No looking back. And it took me one

01:17:45.360 --> 01:17:49.440
[Guest]: year, got it out. That was the second book, The Quest Continues, Lost Heritage of Sikh Legacy in

01:17:49.440 --> 01:17:54.560
[Guest]: Pakistan. So that came out. And then I again, the moment the book came out, I was now this time

01:17:54.560 --> 01:17:59.920
[Guest]: again, like the first book catapulted into these public engagements that took place in Pakistan.

01:17:59.920 --> 01:18:03.520
[Guest]: It took me to over a hundred seminars around the world in just about eight months. So the demand

01:18:03.520 --> 01:18:08.720
[Guest]: was there. People just kept moving me. I just kept talking. And it's really in 2018, September,

01:18:08.720 --> 01:18:14.240
[Guest]: that I came back. I didn't know what to do because this space that I'm in, creative space, which a

01:18:14.240 --> 01:18:19.280
[Guest]: lot of creative people go through, it's what I remember. I recall Shiv Kumar Batalvi, who's a

01:18:19.280 --> 01:18:25.120
[Guest]: Punjabi poet, talks about this concept in a poetry about birha. Virha, as we call it in Punjabi,

01:18:25.120 --> 01:18:32.560
[Guest]: say birha. And virha is that intense pain of separation from your purpose. I mean, virha,

01:18:32.560 --> 01:18:36.480
[Guest]: actually in esoteric language, is talked about intense pain of separation from the divine.

01:18:36.480 --> 01:18:40.480
[Guest]: But for me, the divine was my work. And when that intense pain of separation is there,

01:18:40.480 --> 01:18:45.680
[Guest]: because the purpose is lost, the pain becomes very, very intense. And this pain is what drives

01:18:45.680 --> 01:18:50.080
[Guest]: the creative process. Every time I've seen in this creative, in that corporate treadmill,

01:18:50.080 --> 01:18:53.680
[Guest]: I used to just go straight. Here, it's a sine curve. You go, you create something and go inside

01:18:53.680 --> 01:18:58.800
[Guest]: a valley. And that pain becomes so large that you then catapult again and takes you even to a higher

01:18:58.800 --> 01:19:02.640
[Guest]: pinnacle. How long can you do it? I don't know. But the pain, the deeper it is, the more you'll

01:19:02.640 --> 01:19:08.880
[Guest]: catapult. And I went into a painful process again after my second book. And the catapulting of that

01:19:08.880 --> 01:19:13.440
[Guest]: was basically, I was aware of the first phase, after my first book, that it was a painful

01:19:13.440 --> 01:19:17.280
[Guest]: experience. And I was trying to keep myself busy. And in the making of the second book,

01:19:17.280 --> 01:19:22.800
[Guest]: I had some video footage, thanks to Salman Alam Khan, who was deputed by the establishment to

01:19:22.800 --> 01:19:27.360
[Guest]: follow me into some of the forts, just for the forts. And he told me that, Amardeep Sahib,

01:19:27.360 --> 01:19:30.880
[Guest]: aap kuch bol diya karein, aap creative vande hain, you're a creative person, I'm a creative person,

01:19:30.880 --> 01:19:34.240
[Guest]: aap bol diya karein, my job is not to do a documentary on you, I'm just following you,

01:19:34.240 --> 01:19:38.080
[Guest]: right? But you know what, the data can be used somewhere. And the data fell on my lap. It was

01:19:38.080 --> 01:19:42.480
[Guest]: again a divine intervention, divine gift on my lap. But I had not acted on that data for one and

01:19:42.480 --> 01:19:45.840
[Guest]: a half years. And I came back after my second book, I started looking at the data just to keep

01:19:45.840 --> 01:19:50.560
[Guest]: my mind busy. And I saw a story emerging from it. And I took the music, I took my own feelings,

01:19:50.560 --> 01:19:54.720
[Guest]: and I stitched it together. A novice trying to make a documentary, I learned it. And I all

01:19:54.720 --> 01:19:58.960
[Guest]: stitched it together on my own. And we created two documentaries, which became Peering Soul,

01:19:58.960 --> 01:20:04.240
[Guest]: which takes the viewer in a 50-minute journey to non-traditional sites of spiritual sites

01:20:04.240 --> 01:20:09.040
[Guest]: abandoned across Pakistan. This documentary is not yet fully released on YouTube. I am

01:20:09.040 --> 01:20:13.120
[Guest]: going to probably release it in the third quarter of this year. But we have released the second

01:20:13.120 --> 01:20:17.440
[Guest]: documentary, which is Peering Warrior. That's a 35-minute documentary, which takes the viewer

01:20:17.440 --> 01:20:22.880
[Guest]: across the forts of the Sikhera, where our history had churned right up to the Afghanistan border.

01:20:22.880 --> 01:20:26.560
[Guest]: And some of the footage has never been seen before. So that documentary is there on the

01:20:26.560 --> 01:20:30.960
[Amit Varma]: YouTube. If you search for Peering Warrior, you'll find it. It'll be linked from the show notes as

01:20:30.960 --> 01:20:35.760
[Guest]: indeed the books will be as well. Peering Warrior documentary got completed and Peering

01:20:35.760 --> 01:20:41.600
[Guest]: Soul. So Peering Warrior is there. And thereafter this two documentaries getting completed, my mind

01:20:41.600 --> 01:20:46.800
[Guest]: now was again empty, right? And I'm saying what to do. And that's where very quickly this thought

01:20:46.800 --> 01:20:52.240
[Guest]: manifested because I was already mentally prepared because I knew the narrative of Nanak. And I said

01:20:52.240 --> 01:20:56.880
[Guest]: to myself this question, the skill set that I've developed is good to be aware of. What

01:20:56.880 --> 01:21:01.360
[Guest]: corporate has taught me is it's good to be knowing your strengths and your skills. No point going

01:21:01.360 --> 01:21:04.640
[Guest]: around and beating around the bush, life is too short, right? The skill that I developed in the

01:21:04.640 --> 01:21:11.600
[Guest]: last five years was going into hard to access zones and making things happen to build a narrative.

01:21:11.600 --> 01:21:17.600
[Guest]: That's the skill set at the basic level. So I asked myself, this was January 2019,

01:21:17.600 --> 01:21:22.240
[Guest]: we started this project. I asked myself this question, Guru Nanak travelled far and wide,

01:21:22.240 --> 01:21:29.440
[Guest]: 70% of his region is today in conflict zones. He's travelled far and wide across India, Pakistan,

01:21:29.440 --> 01:21:35.600
[Guest]: Afghanistan, Iraq, Iran, Saudi, Tibet, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka. If you look at the broad canvas,

01:21:35.600 --> 01:21:40.640
[Guest]: 70% of the zone is not accessible today. Pakistan you can go to Nankana Sahib, Panja Sahib,

01:21:40.640 --> 01:21:44.720
[Guest]: Kartarpur Sahib, three traditional Gurudwaras. But Nanak's narrative is not about the three

01:21:44.720 --> 01:21:49.120
[Guest]: Gurudwaras. Nanak's narrative is about him going to Bahauddin Zakaria Shrine, him going to Hingol

01:21:49.120 --> 01:21:53.360
[Guest]: Raj Mandir on his way to Mecca and all those aspects we need to bring in. So I started saying,

01:21:53.360 --> 01:21:58.560
[Guest]: you know what, if my skill set is to get inside these hard to access zones, can I go once again

01:21:58.560 --> 01:22:03.280
[Guest]: and bring together this narrative? And that's how this whole thing started, that I catapulted

01:22:03.280 --> 01:22:09.040
[Guest]: myself last year in January into a journey that today we are performing. It's been now good 16

01:22:09.040 --> 01:22:13.600
[Guest]: months on the road. And it's in the making of Allegria Tapestry Guru Nanak's travels. And I'll

01:22:13.600 --> 01:22:17.600
[Amit Varma]: stop there. And maybe we can talk more about it later. Yeah, I want to come back to that later.

01:22:17.600 --> 01:22:22.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I find that whole project incredibly fascinating. But I have a few more questions about

01:22:22.720 --> 01:22:27.840
[Amit Varma]: your travels through Pakistan. And one of them is this, that a lot of your photographs and by the

01:22:27.840 --> 01:22:31.280
[Amit Varma]: way, your photography is absolutely excellent. I mean, it's hard for me to believe that you're

01:22:31.280 --> 01:22:36.080
[Amit Varma]: a self-taught or an amateur or whatever, because this is beautiful. And a lot of them are of

01:22:36.080 --> 01:22:41.440
[Amit Varma]: buildings and architecture and details of those. And it struck me that a lot of these are buildings

01:22:41.440 --> 01:22:45.440
[Amit Varma]: and architecture that you have first read about. And, you know, and then you see them with your

01:22:45.440 --> 01:22:50.000
[Amit Varma]: own eyes. For example, you've, you know, quoted Baron Carl Hugel's description of the Wazirabad

01:22:50.000 --> 01:22:53.760
[Amit Varma]: Palace, and then you're actually there and you're seeing it with your own eyes. And in some cases,

01:22:53.760 --> 01:22:58.640
[Amit Varma]: they're very dilapidated. They're in ruins. In some cases, they are being maintained and,

01:22:58.640 --> 01:23:03.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, and in some places they don't even sort of exist. How is your sort of reaction to that?

01:23:03.920 --> 01:23:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Are you reorienting your picture of Sikh Pakistan all the time as you travel through it, you know?

01:23:10.000 --> 01:23:15.520
[Guest]: First of all, let's correct this. I don't think I had read more than 15% of the monuments.

01:23:15.520 --> 01:23:21.200
[Guest]: So, I had read about, maybe it's a 15 to 20%. So, of course, I've read about the Attock Fort,

01:23:21.200 --> 01:23:24.480
[Guest]: but I've not seen the Attock Fort. I don't know what Attock Fort looks like, right?

01:23:24.480 --> 01:23:28.640
[Guest]: I know about Jamrud, but I can only imagine what Jamrud is. I've never seen it.

01:23:28.640 --> 01:23:35.840
[Guest]: Right? Okay. I've read about some of the Gurdwaras, Lahore Fort, some of the Gurdwaras,

01:23:35.840 --> 01:23:40.480
[Guest]: historical Gurdwaras, period. And I know about what my intangible culture that my parents used

01:23:40.480 --> 01:23:45.440
[Guest]: to talk about, or what we have seen the strands from my youth days and where we are today.

01:23:46.000 --> 01:23:50.800
[Guest]: I'm aware of these things, but that's all it is. As you get into the country, you are not going

01:23:50.800 --> 01:23:54.240
[Guest]: with something that you know. You're going with an open crucible, with an empty crucible.

01:23:54.240 --> 01:24:00.160
[Guest]: It's a crucible of passion. And then the divine starts filling it up. In that moment,

01:24:00.160 --> 01:24:03.120
[Guest]: you start observing it. Then when you come back and then you start looking at research

01:24:03.120 --> 01:24:08.080
[Guest]: around it here and there, how do I fill it up? And therefore, in some of the places,

01:24:08.080 --> 01:24:12.000
[Guest]: I can't tell you what the monument is about. I can't because I'm not a historian. I don't have

01:24:12.000 --> 01:24:16.080
[Guest]: the facts. I don't have any published sources that are talking about it. So, I'm making the

01:24:16.080 --> 01:24:19.760
[Guest]: most of telling you what I'm observing, because that can become a layer of history in time to

01:24:19.760 --> 01:24:24.880
[Guest]: come. Wherever there's history available, I've quoted it, right? So, that's how one goes through

01:24:24.880 --> 01:24:31.280
[Amit Varma]: it. And how do you warn against a tendency to try and romanticize what you're seeing? Like,

01:24:31.280 --> 01:24:35.360
[Amit Varma]: to just kind of put that in perspective, I traveled through Pakistan when I was covering

01:24:35.360 --> 01:24:40.240
[Amit Varma]: the cricket tour of 2006. And in fact, I, you know, went to the Gurdwara in Peshawar as well.

01:24:40.240 --> 01:24:44.960
[Amit Varma]: But while I was traveling, one tendency I noticed in myself and therefore tried to watch against

01:24:44.960 --> 01:24:50.080
[Amit Varma]: was the tendency to exoticize everything, to see significance in everything. You know, while for

01:24:50.080 --> 01:24:54.800
[Amit Varma]: the people there, they are just the everyday, they are the everyday and the mundane. And there are,

01:24:54.800 --> 01:24:59.760
[Amit Varma]: of course, two sides to this. One is that an outsider brings with him eyes that look past

01:24:59.760 --> 01:25:04.480
[Amit Varma]: the normalization. So, you can find interesting things which the locals might take for mundane,

01:25:04.480 --> 01:25:10.080
[Amit Varma]: but actually is not. But the other side of it is that you try too hard to imbue meaning into

01:25:10.080 --> 01:25:14.880
[Amit Varma]: everything that you see. And the locals are like, you know, who is this guy who's parachuted down,

01:25:14.880 --> 01:25:18.320
[Amit Varma]: and he's finding this interesting and that interesting with these all our lives.

01:25:18.320 --> 01:25:22.720
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you thought about your own process of looking and how others viewed this?

01:25:22.720 --> 01:25:29.760
[Guest]: So, it's an interesting thing, you know, in my documentary, Peering Soul, I have inserted one

01:25:29.760 --> 01:25:36.080
[Guest]: song, which is very much a feeling of my own state. When I'm at a Jambor village,

01:25:36.080 --> 01:25:39.600
[Guest]: and it's Abhita Parveen's Sufi song, it says,

01:25:47.600 --> 01:25:51.760
[Guest]: You made me a passionate person, you infuse passion in me, and I became passionate.

01:25:52.640 --> 01:25:59.600
[Guest]: Now, in this world of conscious people, so-called conscious inverted, don't make me a piece of

01:25:59.600 --> 01:26:05.360
[Guest]: tamasha is a play or a spectacle. Yeah, don't make me that. Now, that's a very profound feeling I

01:26:05.360 --> 01:26:10.160
[Guest]: had. Because then I would go into the places, people would crowd around me, it would cause a

01:26:10.160 --> 01:26:16.240
[Guest]: sense of disturbance. And then there are places where the intelligence would be after me, places

01:26:16.240 --> 01:26:22.160
[Guest]: where people would not open the gates, the places where people would embrace you, right? Potpourri

01:26:22.160 --> 01:26:28.400
[Guest]: of emotions. But I'm making that statement in that Jambor village, because as I climb up on the

01:26:28.400 --> 01:26:33.120
[Guest]: Gurdwara building, which is broken, I request a person on the other side of the building of the

01:26:33.120 --> 01:26:37.600
[Guest]: Gurdwara to allow me to enter from his home and take a picture. First, he was absolutely closed.

01:26:37.600 --> 01:26:42.640
[Guest]: And to get inside a Muslim's home in that village with a purdah system, suddenly he agreed, and I

01:26:42.640 --> 01:26:46.800
[Guest]: was inside. And I clicked a picture. At the same time, there were two, three people who were

01:26:46.800 --> 01:26:52.720
[Guest]: shouting, get out, get out. But at the same time, the entire village had crowded around there and

01:26:52.720 --> 01:26:57.520
[Guest]: looking at me walking on top. And I looked down and I said, I'm a source of play for them, right?

01:26:57.520 --> 01:27:02.720
[Guest]: Source of tamasha for them. What I'm trying to get at is that in this whole play of things, you go

01:27:02.720 --> 01:27:10.080
[Guest]: through a potpourri of challenges. And therefore, it's hard for you to kind of keep yourself focused

01:27:10.800 --> 01:27:16.080
[Guest]: on what you're trying to do. And I've said this earlier, the idea is to just get as much

01:27:16.080 --> 01:27:21.680
[Guest]: information and get out of that place. So it's hard for me to say that, you know,

01:27:22.480 --> 01:27:26.400
[Guest]: the exact things that I would have done if I was a researcher, if I had free access,

01:27:26.400 --> 01:27:30.160
[Guest]: maybe I would have put a staircase, I would have climbed up, I would have looked at each

01:27:30.160 --> 01:27:34.320
[Guest]: artwork interpreted so differently, I would have spent maybe 10 days in a site.

01:27:34.320 --> 01:27:38.560
[Guest]: But that luxury does not exist. So there are going to be a lot of critiques about my work.

01:27:38.560 --> 01:27:43.680
[Guest]: And I say, you know what, critique it as much as you want to. The fact is, the situation does not

01:27:43.680 --> 01:27:47.680
[Guest]: permit you to do that. Today, the situation might change because you've suddenly opened up the

01:27:47.680 --> 01:27:51.760
[Guest]: Pandora's box about seeing the potential that exists there. And that needs to be seen in the

01:27:51.760 --> 01:27:55.520
[Guest]: context of what you're doing as a leader into this domain. So what you were saying about is when

01:27:55.520 --> 01:28:00.560
[Guest]: you're getting inside, when you went in, you had this whole host of people looking at you and other

01:28:00.560 --> 01:28:05.200
[Guest]: things. And how do you keep yourself aligned to your objective? It's hard, very, very hard,

01:28:05.200 --> 01:28:09.680
[Guest]: very hard. And therefore, you have to be very focused as to why are you here.

01:28:09.680 --> 01:28:14.960
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, also, I think what eyes you're looking at your surroundings through,

01:28:14.960 --> 01:28:20.640
[Amit Varma]: like if you bring eyes that are desperate to find meaning that are a collection of your biases and

01:28:20.640 --> 01:28:26.480
[Amit Varma]: your feelings and your, you know, impressions, then that will influence whatever you're seeing.

01:28:26.480 --> 01:28:30.240
[Amit Varma]: Is that something where you thought that, okay, I you know, you already described that you weren't

01:28:30.240 --> 01:28:34.000
[Amit Varma]: emotional during the, you know, during the process. So was your thing during the process

01:28:34.000 --> 01:28:37.200
[Amit Varma]: of let me document everything now, I will process it later.

01:28:37.200 --> 01:28:40.320
[Guest]: You got to keep in mind, I didn't go to write the first book, I didn't go to write the second book,

01:28:40.320 --> 01:28:44.320
[Guest]: I didn't go to make the documentaries. I was simply observing a mere observer.

01:28:44.320 --> 01:28:46.160
[Amit Varma]: But you were taking all these beautiful photographs.

01:28:46.160 --> 01:28:49.680
[Guest]: I was, I was trained as a photographer out of my quest for five years,

01:28:49.680 --> 01:28:53.920
[Guest]: when I was writing for magazines, I'm, I'm capturing the moment for myself,

01:28:54.480 --> 01:28:58.640
[Guest]: not to write a book is when I came back, I felt compelled to write it.

01:28:58.640 --> 01:29:01.760
[Guest]: But that moment, I'm just clicking it, maximizing, just getting out of that place.

01:29:01.760 --> 01:29:03.600
[Amit Varma]: I don't know what I'm going to do with it. I had no idea.

01:29:03.600 --> 01:29:06.960
[Amit Varma]: Would your journey have been different if you had gone there for the purpose of writing?

01:29:06.960 --> 01:29:10.240
[Guest]: That's what I'm saying. So I don't know how different it would have been,

01:29:10.240 --> 01:29:15.520
[Guest]: but I know it would have been much slower. And would it have been as successful? Maybe not.

01:29:15.520 --> 01:29:20.640
[Guest]: Because when you go in as a researcher, your mindset is, I'm going to now study this monument,

01:29:20.640 --> 01:29:23.600
[Guest]: I want to look at 10 things. And I'm not a researcher from that context. I'm trying to

01:29:23.600 --> 01:29:26.800
[Guest]: document, I'm just trying to feel things, right, and get out, right. And I have made

01:29:26.800 --> 01:29:30.240
[Guest]: something compelling out of that. If I was going there as a researcher, let's say I was on a grant

01:29:30.240 --> 01:29:34.320
[Guest]: or let's say going through a university, I would be on a very different frame of mind. In 30 days,

01:29:34.320 --> 01:29:38.080
[Guest]: instead of 36 cities and villages, probably I would have done four. A book would have gone so

01:29:38.080 --> 01:29:42.480
[Guest]: deep inside a subject. But this is about a bandwidth, which is horizontal.

01:29:42.480 --> 01:29:46.000
[Amit Varma]: This is breadth more than depth. And you're building a layer for others.

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:49.680
[Guest]: I'm building a layer. There's a lot of depth if you really want to see it in terms of

01:29:49.680 --> 01:29:54.640
[Guest]: Pakistan and Sikh legacy perspective. There's a lot of depth in it, but it's still at a wider

01:29:55.520 --> 01:30:01.200
[Guest]: horizontal space, right? You can pick up Nanak Panthis. I've devoted 110 pages.

01:30:01.200 --> 01:30:05.360
[Guest]: Pick up Nanak Panthis and I always say, I'm in touch with some Pakistanis and I tell them,

01:30:05.360 --> 01:30:08.720
[Guest]: they're quite inspired with the talks that I've done in last Islamabad Literature Festival and

01:30:08.720 --> 01:30:13.200
[Guest]: Karachi Literature Festival. Some academicians, they are saying that we want to study the Nanak

01:30:13.200 --> 01:30:16.960
[Guest]: Panthis culture in Sindh and Balochistan. I said, by all means, do it because I will not

01:30:16.960 --> 01:30:21.520
[Guest]: succeed in doing it. But I've planted the seed in you. I've given you 110 pages.

01:30:22.720 --> 01:30:26.800
[Guest]: Now you get inside it and you start creating the wells inside it to take you deep inside.

01:30:27.440 --> 01:30:31.440
[Guest]: But if you don't create this landscape, which has been absent for seven decades,

01:30:31.440 --> 01:30:35.200
[Guest]: you can't hope that someone's going to drill a well. So I think that's where it is.

01:30:35.200 --> 01:30:40.320
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, now, courtesy you, I'm going to play another audio clip. And this comes from your trip

01:30:40.320 --> 01:30:45.520
[Amit Varma]: to Lahore, where you met these Muslim descendants of Bhai Mardana. Bhai Mardana, of course, was

01:30:45.520 --> 01:30:50.880
[Amit Varma]: Nanak's companion through his travels. So you meet Muslim descendants of his who are in Lahore

01:30:50.880 --> 01:30:56.320
[Amit Varma]: and who've carried on a tradition of doing Shabad Kirtan, even though it's no longer the profession

01:30:56.320 --> 01:31:00.160
[Amit Varma]: as it was for their forefathers. It's no longer what they do. They are laborers elsewhere and

01:31:00.160 --> 01:31:05.040
[Amit Varma]: they're working at construction sites and all that. But they've kind of kept the passion alive.

01:31:05.040 --> 01:31:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And I'll briefly play this audio clip. And for those of you who listen to this podcast as higher

01:31:09.600 --> 01:31:37.440
[Unknown]: speeds, as indeed I do, just for listening to this, please lower it to normal and then play.

01:33:09.600 --> 01:33:18.320
[Amit Varma]: So that was quite moving. And you also sort of I mean, I have two questions. One question is

01:33:18.320 --> 01:33:22.560
[Amit Varma]: that there are these group of people who are Muslims, even though they're descendants of Bhai

01:33:22.560 --> 01:33:26.960
[Amit Varma]: Mardana, and yet they're singing Shabad Kirtan and they don't get paid for it anymore, as their

01:33:26.960 --> 01:33:32.480
[Amit Varma]: forefathers might have. Why are they doing it? Why do these traditions stay alive? What drives them?

01:33:32.480 --> 01:33:40.960
[Guest]: Who you are is your DNA. It cannot be taken away by just one holocaust. You may try and erase that,

01:33:40.960 --> 01:33:45.520
[Guest]: but deeply you are that, right? The more you'll try and erase it, the more the inside will revolt,

01:33:46.400 --> 01:33:51.200
[Guest]: at least for some few people. Now, Bhai Mardana was the companion, a Muslim companion of Guru

01:33:51.200 --> 01:33:56.400
[Guest]: Nanak, who held the Rabab and walked with him in nine countries. And whenever Guru Nanak wanted

01:33:56.400 --> 01:34:00.560
[Guest]: to sing, Mardana would pick up the Rabab and play with him. They were best of friends.

01:34:00.560 --> 01:34:08.400
[Guest]: They were best of friends. 550 years back, Guru Nanak was born. So, do we think that 550 years

01:34:08.400 --> 01:34:12.800
[Guest]: later, there'll be only one family of the descendants of Mardana? Obviously not. There'll

01:34:12.800 --> 01:34:19.360
[Guest]: be many, right? But yet, I can only talk about one right now, right? Or maybe two. What I'm trying to

01:34:19.360 --> 01:34:25.120
[Guest]: say is that the vast number of people have assimilated into many other things, but this

01:34:25.120 --> 01:34:29.440
[Amit Varma]: island of one or two people. They're outliers. So, I'm a bias in a sense. You met them because

01:34:29.440 --> 01:34:34.240
[Guest]: they're outliers. They're outliers and they're holding on because they are, for some reason,

01:34:34.240 --> 01:34:38.000
[Guest]: having that seed planted in their roots, in their DNA, right? That's what is holding them,

01:34:38.000 --> 01:34:42.800
[Guest]: but the majority have moved away. So, I've often asked this question that I've, now we're getting

01:34:42.800 --> 01:34:47.840
[Guest]: into the realm of the making of Aligriya Tapestry of Guru Nanak's Travels, which has been a project

01:34:47.840 --> 01:34:54.320
[Guest]: that we've been working on for the last 16 months. And I was in Pakistan from February to April, May

01:34:54.320 --> 01:35:00.480
[Guest]: last year. And in my earlier trips I've gone, I've always met this family of descendants of

01:35:00.480 --> 01:35:05.600
[Guest]: Bhai Mardana. And I've also had an opportunity of meeting many more people. But what I'm going

01:35:05.600 --> 01:35:10.000
[Guest]: to get at is the fundamental question that I've asked myself in the making of Aligriya Tapestry

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:14.880
[Guest]: of Guru Nanak's Travels, which is a multi-episode documentary on his travels across nine nations.

01:35:14.880 --> 01:35:21.040
[Guest]: I've asked, the entire community moved away of Nanak Panthis from the lands of Indus.

01:35:21.040 --> 01:35:26.640
[Guest]: And yet, is Baba Nanak alive in those lands? Because Baba Nanak as a physical

01:35:28.400 --> 01:35:32.880
[Guest]: body, of course, is no more there. But his thoughts, are they still alive? It's a question

01:35:32.880 --> 01:35:37.280
[Guest]: that you pose yourself. And then I've had this chance to meet many such people. And before I

01:35:37.280 --> 01:35:42.080
[Guest]: get down to the Bhai Mardanas, I want to talk about, I have had the opportunity, which people

01:35:42.080 --> 01:35:51.360
[Guest]: will find very interesting, to sit in congregations every Friday evening, where the Granth Sahib's

01:35:51.360 --> 01:35:58.240
[Guest]: one verse is picked up. And people from the age of 16, boys, young boy and girl from the age of 16

01:35:59.200 --> 01:36:06.320
[Guest]: to the ripened age of 80, discuss one Shabad. Where is this? In Lahore. And they're all Muslims.

01:36:06.320 --> 01:36:12.320
[Guest]: And they're all Muslims. Baba Nanak is yet alive, I firmly believe, in islands, but he's alive.

01:36:12.880 --> 01:36:17.120
[Guest]: People who have love for him, they may be doing it in closed doors. And I've had opportunities to

01:36:17.120 --> 01:36:21.760
[Guest]: go there, sit down. I could not videograph them, because for all valid reasons, I could have

01:36:21.760 --> 01:36:25.600
[Guest]: been respectful. They didn't want to. But when I look at that, I say, oh, he is still here.

01:36:26.240 --> 01:36:31.520
[Guest]: This is beyond faith. This is about Punjabis, beyond faith, Muslims getting together and

01:36:31.520 --> 01:36:38.800
[Guest]: discussing Baba Nanak's Shabads every Friday evening. And then you look at the descendants

01:36:38.800 --> 01:36:44.960
[Guest]: of Bhai Mardana. Bhai Lalji is Jatha. And I remember in 2014, when I went to Lahore first

01:36:44.960 --> 01:36:50.000
[Guest]: time as a Dehradar Sahib Gurdwara, I met the Babaji there, who had come for 10 minutes of Kirtan.

01:36:50.000 --> 01:36:54.080
[Guest]: There was no one sitting there, no audience, and he was doing the Kirtan. And I asked him,

01:36:54.080 --> 01:36:57.600
[Guest]: and I said, I'm deeply touched that, you know, you've kept the tradition alive,

01:36:57.600 --> 01:37:03.120
[Guest]: but I want to go to their home. And they were very warm. And they said, yes, we would love you to

01:37:03.120 --> 01:37:08.480
[Guest]: take you home. But we apologise, we can't take you home. Because since partition, our forefathers

01:37:08.480 --> 01:37:13.840
[Guest]: used to do Kirtan in the Golden Temple Darbar Sahib and Goindwal Sahib in Punjab. The partition

01:37:13.840 --> 01:37:18.320
[Guest]: was so brutal that, you know, we got thrust on this side and the patrons who would hear us all

01:37:18.320 --> 01:37:22.480
[Unknown]: moved on the other side. Basically, Sikhs and Hindus all moved on the other side. So we landed

01:37:22.480 --> 01:37:27.520
[Guest]: in this place, there was no one to hear. And we are living in poverty, we do daily labour, and we

01:37:27.520 --> 01:37:33.360
[Guest]: just make our ends meet. And there is no Sikh who has come to our home till date. And we are afraid

01:37:33.360 --> 01:37:38.880
[Guest]: that if you will come with your turban, people will, our neighbours will pass judgments. I left

01:37:38.880 --> 01:37:43.200
[Guest]: it. I didn't go back. But every time I would go, I would call them up and we would meet outside.

01:37:43.200 --> 01:37:47.440
[Guest]: But you know, in last year, in February 2019, I was there for Guru Nanak's tapestry, Guru Nanak

01:37:47.440 --> 01:37:53.200
[Guest]: Starvels making. And I asked the Baba again, I said, Baba, take me to your home now, we are here for Guru Nanak Starvels.

01:37:53.200 --> 01:37:58.560
[Guest]: And then he had seen me for four, five years. He said, okay, come, let's go. So he took us to his

01:37:58.560 --> 01:38:03.440
[Guest]: home. And on his roof, we sat and we recorded him and his entire family. Which is a recording,

01:38:03.440 --> 01:38:09.440
[Guest]: I just played a while back. Yes. And the beauty of the whole thing is so everyone had crowded on top

01:38:09.440 --> 01:38:14.160
[Guest]: and they were looking at them playing from the roofs in Lahore. And we got a drone picture of

01:38:14.160 --> 01:38:21.120
[Unknown]: them, everyone looking at them, right. So the beauty is that after we left, a week later, the Baba

01:38:21.120 --> 01:38:28.160
[Guest]: calls me up. He says, son, an amazing thing happened. I said, what? He said, no one said

01:38:28.160 --> 01:38:34.320
[Guest]: anything to us. No one complained. Yeah. I said, why should they? Did we do anything wrong?

01:38:34.320 --> 01:38:38.320
[Guest]: We were there as a message of love. You were there to shower love. We were talking about

01:38:38.320 --> 01:38:44.720
[Guest]: positivities, right. He said, no, you don't know. So I said, no, I respect. But he says,

01:38:44.720 --> 01:38:50.160
[Guest]: but the amazing thing is no one has said anything. What happened is that the veil of fear dropped

01:38:50.160 --> 01:38:55.360
[Guest]: that day. And after that, I would find that, you know, last year was the 550th birth anniversary

01:38:55.360 --> 01:38:59.440
[Guest]: of Guru Nanak. A lot of people were coming in. And he would proudly send a picture of every second

01:38:59.440 --> 01:39:02.480
[Unknown]: person coming to his home. He says, oh, the following has come, the following has come,

01:39:02.480 --> 01:39:10.000
[Guest]: following has come. And I would smile and say, we have just broken the barriers, right. So I think

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:17.280
[Guest]: that's the thing that I want to give as a message that when we talk, then we become closer. The

01:39:17.280 --> 01:39:24.000
[Guest]: Radcliffe line has divided us so badly that a composite culture has got cracked. So basically,

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:28.400
[Guest]: I think that's the strand. And, you know, then there are many I've met who are also

01:39:28.400 --> 01:39:33.040
[Guest]: yet learning Kirtan. They do it in their own quarters. They're Muslims. They're learning

01:39:33.040 --> 01:39:39.360
[Guest]: Kirtan. The beauty of Punjab was that there are pockets who would respect the Vedanta,

01:39:39.360 --> 01:39:44.240
[Guest]: respect the Granth Sahib aspect. And there were also many Hindus and Sikhs who would also,

01:39:44.240 --> 01:39:49.520
[Guest]: vice versa, respect the Islamic and Sufi saints. And embrace multiple identities of their

01:39:49.520 --> 01:39:54.320
[Guest]: traditions. So there's a beautiful book. If you go a little bit down from Punjab and into enter

01:39:54.320 --> 01:39:59.040
[Guest]: into Sindh now, there's a beautiful book by, I forget his second name, but it's Ramse. If you

01:39:59.040 --> 01:40:06.640
[Guest]: search for Ramse, and the title is Hindu Muslim Sikh question mark, right? It could be the other

01:40:06.640 --> 01:40:10.000
[Guest]: way around also. It could be Hindu Sikh Muslim. I don't know. I'll link it from the show notes.

01:40:10.000 --> 01:40:14.960
[Guest]: Yeah, it's Hindu Muslim Sikh. It's got a question mark. The question mark in that study is about

01:40:14.960 --> 01:40:20.400
[Guest]: this Gora, this English man who's studying this community of the Nanak Panthis. And he's questioning

01:40:20.400 --> 01:40:24.560
[Guest]: who are they? Are they Hindus? Are they Muslims? Are they Sikhs? Because for them,

01:40:25.520 --> 01:40:31.520
[Guest]: Ya Allah, Hey Ram, Vaheguru, all come in at the moment when they have to say something.

01:40:31.520 --> 01:40:36.080
[Guest]: They're all a part of the culture. So this was the people of Indus belt.

01:40:37.120 --> 01:40:42.800
[Amit Varma]: Another sort of moving piece of music, which I'm going to play now again, is from a singer named

01:40:42.800 --> 01:40:48.880
[Amit Varma]: Salima Khwaja from Lahore. And the backstory of this is that she learned music from a singer

01:40:48.880 --> 01:40:55.040
[Amit Varma]: called Ghulam Chand. And Ghulam Chand was the sole carrier of a musical legacy that he nurtured all

01:40:55.040 --> 01:41:00.640
[Amit Varma]: alone for many, many years, till Salima Khwaja came to learn from him in Lahore. And now she

01:41:00.640 --> 01:41:05.760
[Guest]: carries it forward. Tell me a little bit about what that was. So there were many descendants of

01:41:07.360 --> 01:41:14.320
[Guest]: Bhai Mardana. And we just talked about one family. And then there was another one,

01:41:14.320 --> 01:41:19.840
[Guest]: Bhai Ghulam Chand, who passed away about, I think, six years back. And he used to do Kirtan at the

01:41:20.960 --> 01:41:26.960
[Guest]: Gurdwara in the Goindwal Sahib in East Punjab. And he also got thrust because of the unfortunate

01:41:26.960 --> 01:41:32.480
[Guest]: partition on this side. But I don't see him actually actively performing in places. I've

01:41:32.480 --> 01:41:36.640
[Guest]: not seen much of his recordings actually performing. So he was more of doing it for

01:41:36.640 --> 01:41:41.040
[Guest]: himself. What he was doing for a living, I don't know. But when I stumbled upon him,

01:41:41.040 --> 01:41:46.960
[Guest]: he was very aged. And he was basically doing, there were some people who had found him and

01:41:46.960 --> 01:41:50.960
[Guest]: they were recording him sitting at his home and some private gatherings here and there.

01:41:51.920 --> 01:41:58.400
[Guest]: There are some people who were quite fascinated by his style of singing. So this is Rababi style,

01:41:58.400 --> 01:42:04.400
[Guest]: you know, the Mardana's family style and singing Gurbani, singing Kabir, singing Nanak,

01:42:04.400 --> 01:42:10.720
[Guest]: and so on and so forth. So some of the locals in Pakistan started going to him to learn.

01:42:12.000 --> 01:42:17.360
[Guest]: One of them was Salima. She went to him for learning Kirtan at 15 years of age.

01:42:18.240 --> 01:42:21.680
[Guest]: Not 15 years of age, sorry. She went to learn with him about 15 years back.

01:42:23.760 --> 01:42:29.840
[Guest]: And today, the Baba is no longer there. He's passed away. But Salima has learned that tradition

01:42:29.840 --> 01:42:37.280
[Guest]: and taken it forward. So to me, this is Bhai Mardana's DNA, which did not pass through the

01:42:37.280 --> 01:42:43.280
[Guest]: blood lineage, has found another place to be seated in. It lives on in the culture. Yeah,

01:42:43.280 --> 01:42:50.320
[Guest]: and it's found in the lady. It's crossing genders now. So Guru Nanak's quest continues from two

01:42:50.320 --> 01:42:56.720
[Guest]: males traveling to now in Pakistan, a female now traveling with Baba Nanak in the form of Mardana.

01:42:56.720 --> 01:43:02.400
[Amit Varma]: So I think he's still alive. Let's listen to this piece of music. Once again, if you're listening

01:43:02.400 --> 01:43:30.240
[Unknown]: at a higher speed, just bring it to normal for this. This will be the last such interruption.

01:44:02.560 --> 01:44:06.240
[Amit Varma]: That was beautiful. So tell me, Amardeep, you know, one of the things I noticed when I traveled

01:44:06.240 --> 01:44:12.320
[Amit Varma]: briefly in 2006, so obviously I was essentially just a tourist, is how warm the people were,

01:44:12.320 --> 01:44:17.520
[Amit Varma]: by and large. On your travels where you actually traveled much deeper and you were going from

01:44:17.520 --> 01:44:22.480
[Amit Varma]: village to village, town to town almost, how did the people treat you and how did they treat your

01:44:22.480 --> 01:44:28.880
[Guest]: quest? Let's try and answer this at a stratospheric level first. I think everywhere, and we've traveled

01:44:28.880 --> 01:44:33.920
[Guest]: far and wide in different countries. I think first and foremost, the principle is as you think,

01:44:33.920 --> 01:44:39.840
[Guest]: so you attract. So I think before we ask how people treated you, I think we need to ask how

01:44:39.840 --> 01:44:44.640
[Guest]: you treated the people. Because if you treated them well enough, they will respond the same way.

01:44:45.520 --> 01:44:50.080
[Guest]: People want to live together. People want to hug each other. People want to be closer to each

01:44:50.080 --> 01:44:54.800
[Guest]: other. People want to understand each other's stories. The pain is not mine. The pain is theirs

01:44:54.800 --> 01:45:00.560
[Guest]: too. The pain is yours too. We are all collectively impacted with it. And if you can understand that

01:45:00.560 --> 01:45:06.000
[Guest]: from a humane perspective, why will people not connect with you? I think that's the principle

01:45:06.000 --> 01:45:12.000
[Guest]: that we need to first understand. If you're going into research work like this, you're going to go

01:45:12.000 --> 01:45:15.520
[Guest]: deep inside. You're going to go deep inside where others are not going. If you go to Lahore,

01:45:16.160 --> 01:45:20.000
[Guest]: oh, a Sikh coming into the turban, or you coming in from India, of course, you know,

01:45:20.000 --> 01:45:24.960
[Guest]: that's like more like a hullaballah, you know, just Mela kind of a thing. Now you're going deep

01:45:24.960 --> 01:45:30.640
[Guest]: inside villages. That's where the true element will come out, right? By and large, people want

01:45:30.640 --> 01:45:36.320
[Guest]: to embrace each other. Beyond faith, beyond religion, as humans, we want to associate with

01:45:36.320 --> 01:45:40.480
[Guest]: each other. Our conditioning might have to be dropped because we might have certain conditioning,

01:45:40.480 --> 01:45:44.240
[Guest]: this is not right, it's wrong, but all that will drop as you start gaining confidence. So people

01:45:44.240 --> 01:45:49.120
[Guest]: are good by nature, but it's all about how you think. But having said that, I think the job is

01:45:49.120 --> 01:45:54.880
[Guest]: not easy. Because people want to live together, but the sovereign nations and the politics of it

01:45:54.880 --> 01:46:01.840
[Guest]: and what we've created, and for all fair reasons, the fear factors. Sort of narratives we feed our

01:46:01.840 --> 01:46:06.720
[Guest]: people. Yeah. And that comes from a political aspect, right? There are people who get paid

01:46:06.720 --> 01:46:11.680
[Guest]: to do their jobs of keeping a watch on you and other things. Maybe that person who's keeping a

01:46:11.680 --> 01:46:16.480
[Guest]: watch on me, when I sit down for a cup of tea, he will drop his guard and he'll become the same

01:46:16.480 --> 01:46:20.160
[Guest]: person, but he's doing a job. You've got to understand that he's doing a job. And that's

01:46:20.160 --> 01:46:24.480
[Guest]: in both sides of the border. They have a job to do. So that's one aspect. That's where the problems

01:46:24.480 --> 01:46:29.600
[Guest]: start coming in. But deep down, they're also human beings. Having said that, when you start peeling

01:46:29.600 --> 01:46:35.680
[Guest]: the layers and start going down, most of the experiences of people going to Pakistan in our

01:46:35.680 --> 01:46:42.560
[Guest]: domain is in Punjab. And you also said you've been to Lahore, maximum Peshawar, it's just a bit off,

01:46:42.560 --> 01:46:47.760
[Guest]: right? But you will find in, let's say in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, there's a cultural sensitivity that

01:46:47.760 --> 01:46:52.560
[Guest]: comes in. Punjabi by nature are more welcoming, you know, Punjab will be, you know, you feel at

01:46:52.560 --> 01:46:58.000
[Guest]: home. But when you go to Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, the cultural aspect starts coming in. The barriers,

01:46:58.000 --> 01:47:03.120
[Guest]: not that people are, people are very nice, but the barrier is there to break that.

01:47:03.120 --> 01:47:05.680
[Guest]: They're speaking Pashto instead of Urdu to begin with.

01:47:05.680 --> 01:47:09.040
[Guest]: Even if you start, let's say there are people who speak in Urdu, even if you're speaking in Urdu,

01:47:09.040 --> 01:47:12.560
[Guest]: it takes a little bit more effort to break the barrier. People are nice, but it'll take a little

01:47:12.560 --> 01:47:15.600
[Guest]: bit. And then the cultural sensitivity, you just can't barge into anyone's home and stuff like

01:47:15.600 --> 01:47:20.640
[Guest]: that. So that becomes a bit of a barrier. I think Kashmir is a bit of an interesting space because

01:47:20.640 --> 01:47:24.320
[Guest]: Kashmir hasn't been in turmoil state for long enough. So Kashmir, I break it down into two

01:47:24.320 --> 01:47:28.800
[Guest]: kinds of people. One is Baltistan, where I've had a lot of chance to go. Baltistan, the Balti people,

01:47:28.800 --> 01:47:34.080
[Guest]: very nice people, very nice. It's not impacted by the Kashmir issue of the partition, you know.

01:47:34.080 --> 01:47:38.320
[Guest]: I mean, the claiming of territories might be there, but people are not impacted by the crossfires

01:47:38.320 --> 01:47:42.960
[Guest]: and other things. Very nice people. It's the Kashmir where my forefathers were from,

01:47:42.960 --> 01:47:48.720
[Guest]: Muzaffarabad, which is right on the LOC, just next to it, right? Now there is a swapping of

01:47:48.720 --> 01:47:55.360
[Guest]: population. There is bad blood that has flown in for long enough. There is doubt, there is suspicion.

01:47:57.440 --> 01:48:02.480
[Guest]: So I've not had major interactions then. I can't say any negative interaction, but neither have I

01:48:02.480 --> 01:48:08.800
[Guest]: had any memorable, positive interaction to talk about. And then you go into Sindh. It becomes

01:48:08.800 --> 01:48:14.960
[Guest]: very interesting that in Sindh, as I said, Hindu, Muslims, Sikh, question mark, Ramsay's work. These

01:48:14.960 --> 01:48:18.160
[Guest]: are people, whether they are Muslims or they're Hindus or whatever they are, they are the Nanak

01:48:18.160 --> 01:48:23.600
[Guest]: Panthis. They're all composite. Very interesting breed of people, the Sindhis are. Very interesting,

01:48:23.600 --> 01:48:28.160
[Guest]: least understood, very interesting people. But now from the Northern and Central Sindh,

01:48:28.160 --> 01:48:32.720
[Guest]: now you come down to a place called Karachi where the population swap happened in 1947.

01:48:32.720 --> 01:48:38.000
[Guest]: Who is the inhabitant of Karachi? It's people from UP and Bihar who came inside and that's where the

01:48:38.000 --> 01:48:43.440
[Guest]: politics of the nation started. So they came in there. Now, let's not forget when partition

01:48:43.440 --> 01:48:49.040
[Guest]: happened, the cleansing happened on both the sides. The UP-Bihar people who came to Karachi

01:48:49.600 --> 01:48:55.040
[Guest]: in the period of July, August, September, their story is not about what happened to Punjab.

01:48:55.040 --> 01:49:02.080
[Guest]: Where did it start from? It starts from, we moved towards our homeland in Karachi and from Punjab,

01:49:02.080 --> 01:49:05.840
[Guest]: in the East Punjab, they faced massacres too because there was massacres happening in West

01:49:05.840 --> 01:49:12.400
[Guest]: Punjab. It was a tit for tat. So their impressions that have come down through the generation is that

01:49:12.400 --> 01:49:18.720
[Guest]: we faced this onslaught on us when we were passing through Punjab. But that memory is ingrained

01:49:18.720 --> 01:49:24.240
[Guest]: somewhere is my experience. When I talk to people, they're nice, they're all great, but there's a

01:49:24.240 --> 01:49:29.120
[Guest]: memory which is there. It's a conditioned memory. No one has a historical understanding of

01:49:29.120 --> 01:49:34.800
[Guest]: what led to the partition of Punjab. Where did it start from? What's the root cause? Because they

01:49:34.800 --> 01:49:40.160
[Guest]: were coming from UP-Bihar, which is far away. Their narrative starts, I got, my father or my

01:49:40.160 --> 01:49:43.840
[Guest]: grandfather experienced this in East Punjab. The narrative starts from there. So there's a

01:49:45.360 --> 01:49:49.120
[Amit Varma]: mistrust deep down, potentially could be there. And I guess the first time they meet you,

01:49:49.120 --> 01:49:53.360
[Amit Varma]: they're not looking at you as an individual per se, but there's all this baggage of that past,

01:49:53.360 --> 01:49:58.240
[Guest]: which is sort of there. So that's how I would define it. So there's a stratospheric level.

01:49:58.240 --> 01:50:03.600
[Guest]: And then by and large, whichever place they may be from, it's how you think that's what you'll

01:50:03.600 --> 01:50:07.120
[Guest]: attract. I think that's the principle. But then these are layers inside it. And that's what I

01:50:07.120 --> 01:50:11.920
[Guest]: just want to expand on. And the same layers in India also. Each state will have a different layer,

01:50:11.920 --> 01:50:15.120
[Guest]: different thinking. UP-Bihar is different than Punjab and South India and everything.

01:50:15.120 --> 01:50:20.400
[Guest]: It's the same thing. But by and large in India, why would someone not live and embrace a person

01:50:20.400 --> 01:50:25.840
[Guest]: without, irrespective of his religion or faith, right? Same thing. And you have another really

01:50:25.840 --> 01:50:29.920
[Amit Varma]: nice story about how you went to the Daftu Gurdwara and this gentleman came to you and said,

01:50:29.920 --> 01:50:33.360
[Amit Varma]: listen, I'm too poor to give you a gift, but I really want to give you something. So here's a

01:50:33.360 --> 01:50:43.040
[Unknown]: pouch of opium. Did you take it? So certain things are kept secret, right? I have taken opium. I have

01:50:43.040 --> 01:50:46.800
[Unknown]: taken even higher drugs than opium. I'm on synthetic drug because these passions are driven

01:50:46.800 --> 01:50:53.920
[Unknown]: by druggy state. I'm just joking. But these are even a higher dose of opium, right? I'm on a drug

01:50:53.920 --> 01:50:58.880
[Unknown]: state to do this work where you're risking your life. The high of the work. Yeah. It's like,

01:50:59.440 --> 01:51:04.320
[Unknown]: I don't need an opium, which grows inside the poppy. My opium is something else, right?

01:51:05.360 --> 01:51:09.200
[Guest]: So just coming to that, there are two very interesting things happened in Daftu.

01:51:09.200 --> 01:51:13.600
[Guest]: It's an abandoned Gurdwara. Not abandoned, people are living inside it. What happened,

01:51:13.600 --> 01:51:17.280
[Guest]: unfortunately, in partition is that you've got to put the landscape correct. You know,

01:51:17.280 --> 01:51:22.560
[Guest]: both the sides suffered. Islamic legacy got wiped out of East Punjab. Hindu and Sikh legacy got

01:51:22.560 --> 01:51:26.800
[Guest]: wiped out. Jain legacy, no one talks about it. Entire Thakpur Kar is filled with Jain site.

01:51:26.800 --> 01:51:30.480
[Guest]: I always say to Pakistan, if you really want to develop your potential,

01:51:31.360 --> 01:51:36.160
[Guest]: also look at not just the Hindu and Sikh aspects. Don't look at Katas Raj and Kartarpur only.

01:51:36.160 --> 01:51:42.000
[Guest]: Look at the huge amount of Jain temples, which are lying abandoned. It's a huge legacy that

01:51:42.000 --> 01:51:45.840
[Guest]: needs to be also brought on the forefront. But you need to understand who these are,

01:51:45.840 --> 01:51:49.200
[Guest]: because you've forgotten, not understood them, right? So when partition happened,

01:51:50.160 --> 01:51:55.280
[Guest]: and people came from East Punjab, there was a humanitarian crisis. You needed a roof on their

01:51:55.280 --> 01:52:01.680
[Guest]: heads. You needed food. People were on their own. They went whatever they got. Gurdwaras typically

01:52:01.680 --> 01:52:06.240
[Guest]: are congregational, and they have huge space. Temples typically are small plinth areas.

01:52:06.800 --> 01:52:10.880
[Guest]: So they could not host people inside, right? Abandoned structures. A lot of people moved

01:52:10.880 --> 01:52:14.080
[Guest]: inside Gurdwaras and made them their homes, especially in remote areas.

01:52:14.080 --> 01:52:19.520
[Guest]: Daftu is one such Gurdwara. It's a fortress-like Gurdwara made from thin bricks, which dates back

01:52:19.520 --> 01:52:23.840
[Guest]: to, which points towards Ranjit Singh's period. Beautiful structure, beautiful fresco works,

01:52:23.840 --> 01:52:29.280
[Guest]: but it's in a bad state now. So I went in there. First and foremost, this huge gathering of the

01:52:29.280 --> 01:52:36.800
[Guest]: villagers came by, right? And someone asked me at the entrance, Sardar Sahib, what is written on top?

01:52:36.800 --> 01:52:44.960
[Guest]: And it was Guru Nanak's verse of Japji, God is one, right? Truth. He's truth, right? He's the

01:52:44.960 --> 01:52:48.160
[Guest]: creator and so on and so forth. So I basically then was standing there and described to the

01:52:48.160 --> 01:52:53.200
[Guest]: person. I said, this is saying that Allah is one. Yeah. I have to talk in their language.

01:52:53.200 --> 01:52:57.840
[Guest]: And then I went inside and this man who's staying inside the Gurdwara, he comes to me and

01:52:57.840 --> 01:53:02.720
[Guest]: is a very emotional. One of those few moments when I was really emotionally touched. He tells me

01:53:02.720 --> 01:53:08.880
[Guest]: in Punjabi, he says, he holds, folds his hand, he says, I apologize. Say it in the original Punjabi

01:53:08.880 --> 01:53:15.840
[Guest]: if you want to. Yeah. So he says, Sardar Sahib, maafi mangde hain. Saade kol uthe sirf do

01:53:15.840 --> 01:53:22.000
[Guest]: waqt di roti seegi. Ish Punjab, from where he came. Saade kol uthe sirf do waqt di roti seegi.

01:53:22.640 --> 01:53:28.640
[Guest]: Gadar vich asi ithe aage, in partition we came here. Gadar vich asi ithe aage, pinda pinda firde

01:53:28.640 --> 01:53:35.600
[Guest]: rahe, te daftu aa poche. Gurdwara khaadi seega, asi andar badge. Asi taan to ithe rahe hain.

01:53:35.600 --> 01:53:42.080
[Guest]: Maafi mangde hain, taadi imarat nahi sambhal sake. He's saying, in the Holocaust, we came from

01:53:42.080 --> 01:53:46.480
[Guest]: East Punjab. We went through different villages and finally we came to Daftu. And we took place

01:53:46.480 --> 01:53:52.960
[Guest]: inside shelter inside this Gurdwara. And I really apologize that I could not maintain your Gurdwara.

01:53:52.960 --> 01:53:58.880
[Guest]: Because asi uthe ek waqt di roti kamande se, athe aaj bhi ek waqt di roti kama rahe hain. We were

01:53:58.880 --> 01:54:03.840
[Guest]: only earning one bread there and one bread we earn here. We are still poor, but we could not

01:54:03.840 --> 01:54:12.240
[Guest]: maintain it. That tells you the humane aspect of this entire crisis. He feels it, right? That

01:54:12.240 --> 01:54:17.440
[Guest]: someone has come. And then as I'm coming out and I'm leaving, there's a person comes in, again

01:54:17.440 --> 01:54:24.000
[Unknown]: another old man, right? Whom I'm talking about. He comes in and he holds my hand before I'm leaving.

01:54:24.000 --> 01:54:31.040
[Guest]: He says, Sardar sahib, mere naal aao. He says, Sardar ji, come with me. I walk with him on the side.

01:54:31.040 --> 01:54:37.280
[Guest]: I thought he's going to talk about something. And he opens his, from his shirt, he opens a small

01:54:37.280 --> 01:54:44.240
[Guest]: knot. And he says, sade kul den waste kuch nahi hain. Thodi ji afeem hai laelo tusi. You know, I have

01:54:44.240 --> 01:54:48.640
[Unknown]: nothing to give you. The little opium lying here, please take it. And I started laughing, right?

01:54:49.840 --> 01:54:55.280
[Amit Varma]: I was touched by that moment. It was beautiful. It was beautiful. Let's talk about your current

01:54:55.280 --> 01:55:00.720
[Amit Varma]: project now, retracing the steps of Guru Nanak and his travels. First of all, how do you determine

01:55:00.720 --> 01:55:05.680
[Amit Varma]: where Guru Nanak went? Because he didn't write about it himself. Yeah, it's a good question. So

01:55:05.680 --> 01:55:13.120
[Guest]: you are embarking on a massive project in 550 years after his life, right? And we are trying to

01:55:13.120 --> 01:55:18.080
[Guest]: retrace his footsteps through visual documentation. I'm very clear in my mind. I am a human,

01:55:18.080 --> 01:55:23.680
[Guest]: I will make mistakes. But I don't want to create new history. Because I know the beautiful,

01:55:23.680 --> 01:55:30.880
[Guest]: pristine philosophy of Guru Nanak, which is beyond the tangibles. His first profound verse itself

01:55:30.880 --> 01:55:36.160
[Guest]: talks about the vastness of his philosophy, stands reduced and limited today to tangibles,

01:55:37.040 --> 01:55:42.880
[Guest]: to miracles, to tangibles. All these humans who had powers can do miracles, but that's not

01:55:42.880 --> 01:55:49.840
[Guest]: what their philosophy is about. They are beyond miracles. They, being humans, are transforming

01:55:49.840 --> 01:55:55.920
[Guest]: lives is a miracle by itself. They're teaching someone about how to live is a miracle by itself.

01:55:55.920 --> 01:56:02.560
[Guest]: And yet today, we have reduced him to in this place, he took out water from the well,

01:56:02.560 --> 01:56:07.680
[Guest]: and that place he implanted some impression and this and that. It's all magic and everything.

01:56:07.680 --> 01:56:14.160
[Guest]: His ability to implant an impression in your heart and dig into the wells of your heart

01:56:14.160 --> 01:56:19.200
[Guest]: is forgotten. So there's a big problem on how you're going to present Guru Nanak first at an

01:56:19.200 --> 01:56:27.040
[Guest]: allegoric level. This is allegory, a tapestry of Guru Nanak's travels. A tapestry of Guru Nanak's

01:56:27.040 --> 01:56:30.960
[Guest]: travels is easy to understand. It's like the fabric, the warp and the weft of his travels.

01:56:30.960 --> 01:56:35.360
[Guest]: We can actually link it up. And we'll come to that, how you're going to determine that. But

01:56:35.360 --> 01:56:40.800
[Guest]: the bigger thing is allegory. Allegory is actually a revelation of a hidden meaning.

01:56:41.760 --> 01:56:48.400
[Guest]: Nanak today is not understood. I'm not a preacher. I'm not a theologian. But I have a probing in

01:56:48.400 --> 01:56:52.560
[Guest]: this entire journey that I want to understand Nanak, who he is through these places. Why was

01:56:52.560 --> 01:56:56.960
[Guest]: he traveling? What was he communicating? And that allegoric meaning has to be revealed.

01:56:56.960 --> 01:57:03.920
[Guest]: That he has written. The beauty of Nanak is, unlike Babar, who writes his Babar Nama,

01:57:04.640 --> 01:57:07.200
[Guest]: or unlike Jahangir, who writes Tuzak-e-Jahangiri,

01:57:08.960 --> 01:57:16.880
[Guest]: or unlike Ranjit Singh, who commissions to write Umdat-u-Tariq, Nanak only compiles

01:57:16.880 --> 01:57:22.640
[Guest]: spiritual verses that tell us how to lead a life, the psychology of a life, the inner being.

01:57:22.640 --> 01:57:28.960
[Guest]: And that becomes later on a part of the Granth Sahib. He writes nothing about himself. Nothing.

01:57:29.520 --> 01:57:34.160
[Guest]: And yet you then want to make a documentary on his travels. So where are you going to start from?

01:57:34.160 --> 01:57:38.560
[Guest]: Because if your objective is not to create another new version of Nanak's travel, because

01:57:38.560 --> 01:57:44.000
[Guest]: I sometimes jokingly say that Nanak in today's day is traveling further and further. Even in

01:57:44.000 --> 01:57:48.880
[Guest]: 550 years after his life, every second day in the web university, or in the WhatsApp university,

01:57:48.880 --> 01:57:56.720
[Guest]: or in Facebook, he's reaching newer and newer places. So I think Nanak needs to be left alone.

01:57:57.440 --> 01:58:02.240
[Guest]: We need to understand his philosophy. But yet we are attempting to map out his travels. How are

01:58:02.240 --> 01:58:06.960
[Guest]: we going to do it? You have to then look at what's the documented sources. Now documented sources

01:58:06.960 --> 01:58:11.520
[Guest]: are written by men of faith. And if he has not written it, these are not primary sources.

01:58:12.480 --> 01:58:15.920
[Guest]: Or someone living in his time has not written it, these are not primary sources. The first text

01:58:15.920 --> 01:58:21.280
[Guest]: that appears is by Bhai Gurdas, who writes during the times of the Sikh gurus, but some 50 years

01:58:21.280 --> 01:58:26.640
[Guest]: after his life. But he writes, Guru Nanak and Mardana traveled far and wide. And they went on

01:58:26.640 --> 01:58:32.480
[Guest]: Udasis. Far and wide, but he specifically mentions four places, but he does not say that's what is

01:58:32.480 --> 01:58:35.680
[Guest]: limited to. He travels far and wide, he's acknowledging, but he says he went to Sumer,

01:58:35.680 --> 01:58:43.360
[Guest]: which is Kailash. He went to Baghdad. He went to Makkah. He went to Batala, where the Shivites and

01:58:43.360 --> 01:58:48.240
[Guest]: the Sidhs used to sit. And then he says he traveled far and wide, not big enough to make a narrative

01:58:48.240 --> 01:58:53.920
[Guest]: out of it. So then you move forward in timeline and you come across the first text that the men

01:58:53.920 --> 01:58:59.680
[Guest]: of faith have written, which is known as Janam Sakis. Like the Buddhist Jatakas are there. So

01:58:59.680 --> 01:59:03.920
[Guest]: like that, the Janam Sakis are written by men of faith, but seven to 10 decades after his life.

01:59:03.920 --> 01:59:07.280
[Guest]: You can't throw the baby in the bathtub because that's the only source available to you. You have

01:59:07.280 --> 01:59:11.760
[Guest]: to accept it. There may be human errors inside it, but that's the only source you have, documented

01:59:11.760 --> 01:59:16.000
[Guest]: source. So you take this composite literature written seven to 10 decades after his lifetime,

01:59:17.200 --> 01:59:23.200
[Guest]: and we draw a line there. We said we will make an assimilation of this and take out the journey

01:59:23.200 --> 01:59:28.320
[Guest]: that he did out of this. Later on, texts continue to make him travel further and further and further.

01:59:28.320 --> 01:59:32.960
[Guest]: We've drawn a line at the hundred years. That's it. So we are mapping that and as per that,

01:59:32.960 --> 01:59:40.480
[Guest]: he's traveled to nine countries. Today, in fact, in the 550th year celebration of Guru Nanak's

01:59:40.480 --> 01:59:47.600
[Guest]: travels, there was a book that was released by Indian High Commission in Kathmandu.

01:59:48.560 --> 01:59:54.160
[Guest]: And it's about the Sikh sites in Nepal. And there's a lot of mention there of Guru Nanak

01:59:54.160 --> 01:59:59.360
[Guest]: having come here, coming there, come there, not backed by any old texts. And they're confusing

01:59:59.360 --> 02:00:03.760
[Guest]: it with the Udasi tradition who came in after the fall of the Sikh empire. And Rani Jindan,

02:00:03.760 --> 02:00:10.640
[Guest]: actually, who was the wife of Ranjit Singh, was given refuge by Nepal Naresh. She was captured

02:00:10.640 --> 02:00:15.680
[Guest]: in the Chunar Fort and from where she escapes. Thereafter, a lot of these Udasi shrines come up

02:00:16.320 --> 02:00:21.040
[Guest]: because they have old Granth Sahib, the old handwritten Granth Sahib. Today, people are

02:00:21.040 --> 02:00:25.040
[Guest]: just randomly going and everyone can say anything and they say that Guru Nanak came here and so on

02:00:25.040 --> 02:00:29.600
[Guest]: and so forth. So like that, Guru Nanak has been sent to Rome, to Turkey, to every place. I was

02:00:29.600 --> 02:00:36.320
[Guest]: in Rome and I met the Pope's office and we explored it. There's some reference someone wrote on the

02:00:36.320 --> 02:00:42.640
[Guest]: website. And once you write something that becomes imprinted, right? So 10 years back, something was

02:00:42.640 --> 02:00:50.160
[Guest]: written, 2006, about 13 years back. And some person from the Rome, he's quoted from the Vatican

02:00:50.160 --> 02:00:55.360
[Guest]: and the Pope and his office deny it. We don't have any references here of that. So here you're

02:00:55.360 --> 02:01:00.400
[Guest]: struggling with, someone writes just out of his faith and belief, nothing mentioned in texts of

02:01:00.400 --> 02:01:04.720
[Guest]: 100 years. And then suddenly Guru Nanak has now reached Rome. Today, you find it hard to rationalise.

02:01:04.720 --> 02:01:08.880
[Guest]: So in this whole context, we restricted ourselves to the oldest primary text because there itself,

02:01:08.880 --> 02:01:15.360
[Guest]: if you can document that, it's a huge and humongous task because 70% of the area geographical expanse

02:01:15.360 --> 02:01:19.920
[Guest]: is not accessible because it's all in conflict zones. You will be able to go to three Gurdwaras

02:01:19.920 --> 02:01:23.840
[Guest]: in Pakistan. How will you go into Balochistan? How will you go to Hinglaj? Carry a camera to

02:01:23.840 --> 02:01:30.720
[Guest]: Hinglaj temple? Who's going to allow you? You go behind an Indus region from Indus river in the

02:01:30.720 --> 02:01:35.360
[Guest]: Baltistan area when he's coming from Kailash Mansarovar into Ladakh and then comes into Kashmir

02:01:35.360 --> 02:01:42.160
[Guest]: and from that area, how will you get into behind Kargil? It sounds impossible. Leave alone Iraq

02:01:42.160 --> 02:01:48.480
[Guest]: and Iran. Iraq, Iran, it's a different ballgame. How will you go to Mansarovar and take out a camera

02:01:48.480 --> 02:01:52.240
[Guest]: to film? The Chinese government is not going to allow you. And then from there, walk up to the

02:01:52.240 --> 02:01:56.080
[Guest]: Himachal border or walk up to Pangong Tso on the China side. How are you going to do it?

02:01:56.960 --> 02:02:02.480
[Guest]: It seems impossible. And yet when you walked, it happened. So two questions for you. One is

02:02:02.480 --> 02:02:07.520
[Amit Varma]: obviously clear to me that, you know, Nanak is one of the great travellers of those times,

02:02:07.520 --> 02:02:13.120
[Amit Varma]: but unlike others like Yohun Sang and whoever, who are, you know, Marco Polo, who are celebrated

02:02:13.120 --> 02:02:17.280
[Amit Varma]: as travellers, I think a little less of his travels is known probably because he didn't

02:02:17.280 --> 02:02:21.760
[Amit Varma]: write about it himself. So one question is how did he actually get around? Those are the days

02:02:21.760 --> 02:02:26.240
[Amit Varma]: before sort of mass transport exists. There are no flights, there are no trains, there's none of that.

02:02:27.040 --> 02:02:32.800
[Amit Varma]: How is he getting around from place to place? What is he exactly doing? What is the nature of

02:02:32.800 --> 02:02:39.600
[Amit Varma]: his quest? Like clearly he is engaging in dialogue with all kinds of people to get greater clarity

02:02:39.600 --> 02:02:43.920
[Amit Varma]: and to spread his ideas. What is that process like? And the second question, which we can come

02:02:43.920 --> 02:02:49.120
[Amit Varma]: to later, is that in these times where borders do exist, how did you manage to go to all these

02:02:49.120 --> 02:02:54.880
[Guest]: places? So I don't know whether Nanak was meeting people to spread his ideas. I don't know. Some

02:02:54.880 --> 02:02:59.840
[Guest]: people may not like what I'm saying. Because if we treat Nanak as a human being first, then there's

02:02:59.840 --> 02:03:04.640
[Amit Varma]: a quest that he's on. In fact, one of the places you visited in Pakistan and photograph was Nanak

02:03:04.640 --> 02:03:10.240
[Amit Varma]: Tibba, which is this mound where Nanak compiled the verses of Baba Farid. He collated it. He

02:03:10.240 --> 02:03:15.680
[Guest]: collated it. So it's a quest for understanding from what. Absolutely. So one third of his life,

02:03:15.680 --> 02:03:20.720
[Guest]: he doesn't move out. The other part of his life, the second or the third part of his life,

02:03:21.360 --> 02:03:27.360
[Guest]: he goes on a quest for 22 years. In the last of the three phases of his life, he settles down in

02:03:27.360 --> 02:03:32.800
[Guest]: Kartarpur. My sense is, this is purely my sense, having travelled on these parts, and I've been

02:03:32.800 --> 02:03:37.120
[Guest]: a person on a quest also, when you're travelling, you're meeting so many people, a lot of things,

02:03:38.080 --> 02:03:42.320
[Guest]: you're congregating, you're listening, you're imparting, you're hearing, but it's a two-way

02:03:42.320 --> 02:03:49.680
[Guest]: process. You can't just be giving, giving, giving. It's a two-way process. If you treat Nanak as a

02:03:49.680 --> 02:03:56.240
[Guest]: human being, the process of growth happens by hearing and imparting. Is there a mapping of

02:03:56.240 --> 02:04:01.040
[Amit Varma]: that growth? Like, do we have a sense of how his thinking changed during this quest? Yeah,

02:04:01.040 --> 02:04:05.280
[Guest]: so just let me just complete this. So then you come to the third part of his life, where he

02:04:05.280 --> 02:04:09.280
[Guest]: settled on Kartarpur. I think that's where he started getting a congregation. That's where he

02:04:09.280 --> 02:04:13.840
[Guest]: passed the betan. So I always think about it. Why is it that the Kabir Panthis did not have a

02:04:13.840 --> 02:04:18.000
[Guest]: structured group that following? I mean, theoretically, Kabir Panthis could have also

02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:22.800
[Guest]: formed an empire at one point of time, like the Sikhs did it. I think that military aspect came

02:04:22.800 --> 02:04:27.520
[Guest]: much later. But it was because Nanak and Kabir had one, they were similar, but they did one thing

02:04:27.520 --> 02:04:33.760
[Guest]: different. Nanak passed a leadership betan to the second guru, and betan passed down for 10 gurus.

02:04:33.760 --> 02:04:40.000
[Guest]: Kabir did not pass him. So Kabir only remained at a realm where he was a bit less hardened.

02:04:40.880 --> 02:04:45.760
[Guest]: So what I'm coming to is that Nanak was on a quest, he traveled, and he traveled on a two-way

02:04:45.760 --> 02:04:50.400
[Guest]: process. But where was he traveling is the question. If you look at the structure in his

02:04:50.400 --> 02:04:57.280
[Guest]: mappings, wherever we've been, there is a spiritual congregation in that place where he was going to

02:04:57.280 --> 02:05:06.880
[Guest]: go, of that time. Spiritual congregation either associated with myth, reality, but people were

02:05:06.880 --> 02:05:13.120
[Guest]: coming there. For him, interaction with people was the most important. Whether it was at Haridwar,

02:05:13.120 --> 02:05:17.920
[Guest]: he gave the profound message of, if you're doing shraddh, if you're giving water to your parents

02:05:17.920 --> 02:05:24.240
[Guest]: who passed away, or your forefathers, and if that can reach by putting the water towards the sun

02:05:24.240 --> 02:05:31.120
[Guest]: to that passed away generation, then I can turn the other way around and water my fields in Punjab,

02:05:31.120 --> 02:05:36.000
[Guest]: and this water should reach smaller distance here. So he was trying to rationalize. Basically,

02:05:36.000 --> 02:05:40.880
[Guest]: he was going to places where people would congregate. And that took him then to places

02:05:40.880 --> 02:05:48.080
[Guest]: of Islamic, Sufi, Jain, Buddhist, a lot of Hindu sites, Jogis, and he would congregate with them.

02:05:48.080 --> 02:05:52.240
[Guest]: So when you understand that, then you start questioning, okay, how did he travel then?

02:05:52.240 --> 02:05:57.760
[Guest]: Not a rocket science. Not a rocket science at all. From Punjab, people were traveling to Makkah.

02:05:58.480 --> 02:06:02.800
[Guest]: How were they traveling? There were two routes. One would get them along the Indus,

02:06:02.800 --> 02:06:08.080
[Guest]: maybe get onto a boat, maybe walk down. You can do about 20 kilometers a day.

02:06:09.920 --> 02:06:14.880
[Guest]: And you get down to Sindh. From Sindh, you go via Balochistan into Iran, and then you reach

02:06:14.880 --> 02:06:21.280
[Guest]: to the desert route into Makkah. The other one was you go down into the Arabian Sea and take a

02:06:21.280 --> 02:06:27.200
[Guest]: boat from there and sail into Makkah. Both are possible. People were doing it. So Nanak also did

02:06:27.200 --> 02:06:31.680
[Guest]: that same thing for a certain period of his time. But the difference was that they would come back,

02:06:31.680 --> 02:06:37.040
[Guest]: and he went on the old pilgrimage route to Baghdad, but people from Baghdad would also come.

02:06:37.040 --> 02:06:41.680
[Guest]: From there, he turned into Afghanistan. People would from Afghanistan also go that way. He came

02:06:41.680 --> 02:06:51.040
[Guest]: on that route. People from India would go to Mansarovar, Kailash. From time immemorial,

02:06:51.040 --> 02:06:56.480
[Guest]: they're going. The Sidh used to sit there. The Nath yogis used to sit there. And he went along

02:06:56.480 --> 02:07:02.160
[Guest]: from the Badrinath area, along the passes into Kailash and Mansarovar. It's just a few days'

02:07:02.160 --> 02:07:09.280
[Guest]: trek. People were doing it. Through Shivkila Pass, they went from there. So if you really

02:07:09.280 --> 02:07:16.800
[Guest]: break down his travels, which on a macro level looks like a huge landscape, actually break into

02:07:16.800 --> 02:07:21.920
[Guest]: small chunks, it's all doable. But he was only going to places where spiritualists congregate.

02:07:21.920 --> 02:07:26.320
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it's a 22 years' travel. And do you have a sense of his intellectual evolution

02:07:26.320 --> 02:07:30.480
[Amit Varma]: in this period? Like he's going to all of these places, he's talking to all of these people,

02:07:30.480 --> 02:07:36.160
[Amit Varma]: he's learning, he's assimilating knowledge and ways of thinking. How does this influence what

02:07:36.160 --> 02:07:42.160
[Guest]: Sikhism becomes? It's a hard question for me to answer. And it's getting into a realm of any

02:07:42.160 --> 02:07:48.160
[Guest]: opinion I'll give could touch people on the wrong side. But I'm just saying that if we treat Nanak

02:07:48.160 --> 02:07:56.160
[Guest]: as a human, if we treat, then every human has an evolution process. Nanak was a spiritually

02:07:56.160 --> 02:08:02.320
[Guest]: elevated person right from his childhood. He was having conversations around certain mundane tasks

02:08:02.320 --> 02:08:10.480
[Guest]: about religious practices. Yes, he was absolutely evolved. But him meeting Mardana, and then bringing

02:08:10.480 --> 02:08:15.440
[Guest]: in the musical knowledge, and then the two walking into Islamic sites, Sufi sites, different places,

02:08:16.160 --> 02:08:23.600
[Guest]: of course, he would have assimilated. I'm not comparing myself with any Nanak. I'm not one.

02:08:23.600 --> 02:08:28.880
[Guest]: But I know when I've travelled, the good chunk of my career that I spent in the corporate world,

02:08:28.880 --> 02:08:34.240
[Guest]: where I was meeting people with a different mindset was still making me learn. But this

02:08:34.240 --> 02:08:40.720
[Guest]: path and this journey has made me more learned, more evolved. I'm nowhere near Nanak. But it's

02:08:40.720 --> 02:08:44.800
[Guest]: made me a different person who I am. When you meet and interact with people of different faiths,

02:08:45.360 --> 02:08:49.680
[Guest]: you will understand the quest of Nanak was not Gurdwaras, there were none at that time.

02:08:49.680 --> 02:08:55.440
[Guest]: Quest was something different. And to understand Nanak, you will have to understand Jainism,

02:08:55.440 --> 02:08:58.480
[Guest]: you will have to understand Buddhism, you will have to understand Vedanta, you'll have to

02:08:58.480 --> 02:09:02.640
[Guest]: understand the six philosophical systems, you will have to understand the Nath Jogis,

02:09:02.640 --> 02:09:06.640
[Guest]: you will have to understand the Sufis, you'll have to understand Baba Farid, and so on and so forth.

02:09:06.640 --> 02:09:13.680
[Guest]: So when he goes to Pakpattan, and he sits there, the 11th descendant of the Gaddi Naseen of Baba

02:09:13.680 --> 02:09:18.480
[Guest]: Farid, because Baba Farid was 250 years before him, and beautiful Punjabi verses he writes.

02:09:19.280 --> 02:09:24.000
[Guest]: He collates it. Why does he collate it? Because he finds a similarity in their mindsets.

02:09:24.000 --> 02:09:31.200
[Guest]: In fact, the most valuable contribution in Punjabi poetry of Baba Farid is by Nanak that he collated

02:09:31.200 --> 02:09:37.360
[Guest]: it. This was going through by oral traditions. In fact, all the works of Baba Farid that have

02:09:37.360 --> 02:09:42.640
[Guest]: been done later on in Shahamukhi, which is the Urdu script, much later are all taken from the

02:09:42.640 --> 02:09:50.160
[Guest]: Granth Sahib, because Nanak documented it. Nanak documented Kabir's verses. Bijak came much later,

02:09:50.160 --> 02:09:55.280
[Guest]: which today people say is Bijak is Kabir's work. Go into the Granth Sahib, and there's a repository

02:09:55.280 --> 02:10:01.360
[Guest]: of Kabir's writings. And that's the beauty of what he was doing. So could he be doing that without

02:10:01.360 --> 02:10:06.880
[Amit Varma]: evolving? I find it hard to accept. At one level, I'm thinking Nanak could easily as he traveled,

02:10:06.880 --> 02:10:10.560
[Amit Varma]: have done a podcast called The Seen and The Unseen and documented all these dialogues in

02:10:10.560 --> 02:10:14.880
[Amit Varma]: audio form. But alas, there was no technology back then. So to get back to the second question,

02:10:14.880 --> 02:10:20.560
[Amit Varma]: I ask, at a practical level, like we're recording this on March 12, you decided you'll do India last,

02:10:20.560 --> 02:10:24.240
[Amit Varma]: you are about to finish India, you did all the other countries, you did all the travel,

02:10:24.240 --> 02:10:28.880
[Amit Varma]: you went to these conflict zones, you went to Baluchistan, you went to Iran, Iraq, you went

02:10:28.880 --> 02:10:34.800
[Amit Varma]: everywhere. How was that experience like both in terms of getting permissions and to other places

02:10:34.800 --> 02:10:38.720
[Amit Varma]: where Nanak traveled, where Nanak Panti is simply not there, there's no trace of it, he only happened

02:10:38.720 --> 02:10:45.680
[Guest]: to go there. Traveling into these places is very tough. You cannot retrace Guru Nanak's travels the

02:10:45.680 --> 02:10:50.480
[Guest]: way he traveled. It's impossible today. We're talking about sovereign nations. I cannot travel

02:10:50.480 --> 02:10:55.360
[Guest]: in that sequential manner, but I can get the data and can stitch it so that you and the next

02:10:55.360 --> 02:10:59.520
[Guest]: generation when they're looking at, they see it sequentially. That's the only way it's possible.

02:10:59.520 --> 02:11:02.320
[Guest]: But sovereign nations, there are a lot of ifs and buts, especially if we're trying to do

02:11:02.320 --> 02:11:06.160
[Guest]: photography and videography. Is it going with a team and a crew? When I did my Sikh legacy in

02:11:06.160 --> 02:11:09.680
[Guest]: Pakistan, I just had my camera and I just had my passion. But now you've got to go with a team.

02:11:10.320 --> 02:11:14.640
[Guest]: And that's a very different ballgame. And when you get inside the country, first and foremost,

02:11:14.640 --> 02:11:21.520
[Guest]: the barrier is how will you get inside? How deep can you go? How will you enable it? There's some

02:11:21.520 --> 02:11:25.360
[Guest]: countries where the permission is not going to come to you. You just have to do it as a stealth

02:11:25.360 --> 02:11:30.800
[Guest]: mission. Risk your life and just do it as a stealth mission. Some countries, the permission

02:11:30.800 --> 02:11:35.600
[Guest]: will come to you, but may not come to you deep inside. Some countries, visas will be a big

02:11:35.600 --> 02:11:40.560
[Guest]: problem. I've faced a lot of problems, a lot of visas in many places. India might sound to be the

02:11:40.560 --> 02:11:46.640
[Guest]: easiest, but what one does not realize is that India, I have a Government of India's approval

02:11:46.640 --> 02:11:50.400
[Guest]: from Ministry of Culture, but when you're traveling, every temple has its own management.

02:11:51.600 --> 02:11:57.120
[Unknown]: They don't recognize the Government of India's letter. Right? Everyone's a king out here. Every

02:11:57.120 --> 02:12:00.640
[Guest]: state is different. You might have the Government of India's approval letter from Ministry of

02:12:00.640 --> 02:12:04.640
[Guest]: Culture, but BJP may not be in a power in a certain state. They don't care about that letter.

02:12:04.640 --> 02:12:11.040
[Guest]: So there's this huge mix of challenges and you've got to manage that. Even in a country where life

02:12:11.040 --> 02:12:17.520
[Guest]: is not a threat in India, right? You can imagine how tough it becomes. So that's the first part to

02:12:17.520 --> 02:12:22.960
[Guest]: the question. So your second question was that the Nanak Panthis, were they there, right? Look,

02:12:22.960 --> 02:12:28.080
[Guest]: when Nanak was traveling, the Nanak's panth was not being formed. Nanak in his first part of his

02:12:28.080 --> 02:12:33.120
[Guest]: life was not creating any followership. Second part, he was on a quest. Third part, when he came

02:12:33.120 --> 02:12:38.480
[Guest]: and settled down at Kartarpur, people started flocking around him because he now had immense

02:12:38.480 --> 02:12:43.120
[Guest]: value to offer. I think the panth starts emerging from there. The community starts emerging from

02:12:43.120 --> 02:12:47.680
[Guest]: there. Till then, he's just moving around. He's making an impact. It's the betan that he passes

02:12:47.680 --> 02:12:52.960
[Guest]: on to the second guru and that lasts on for 250 years in the name of Nanak creates a bigger and

02:12:52.960 --> 02:12:58.880
[Guest]: bigger community up till Afghanistan, deep inside India, Maharashtra and so on and so forth. That

02:12:58.880 --> 02:13:05.360
[Amit Varma]: becomes the Nanak Panthis. So, you know, we're kind of running out of time. So my sort of final

02:13:05.360 --> 02:13:12.000
[Amit Varma]: question here would be that, you know, in the process of immersing yourself in Sikh traditions

02:13:12.000 --> 02:13:16.880
[Amit Varma]: or Nanak Panthis traditions, first in Pakistan and now on this entire trip, how has a way that

02:13:16.880 --> 02:13:22.880
[Amit Varma]: you look at your faith changed, your community changed? And if any, what is a message that you'd

02:13:22.880 --> 02:13:27.840
[Amit Varma]: like to sort of give to the Sikh community at this point in time about how they look at their

02:13:27.840 --> 02:13:35.760
[Guest]: own history and their own heritage? Well, I think the learning is only a reaffirmation of the most

02:13:35.760 --> 02:13:42.160
[Guest]: fundamental message of Nanak of oneness. There's nothing different, right? It's just one message,

02:13:42.160 --> 02:13:46.720
[Guest]: simple message of oneness that we are one. And I think it's free to have the ability to

02:13:46.720 --> 02:13:54.640
[Guest]: understand that all can coexist in a bouquet of oneness. That's the only message that I'll take,

02:13:54.640 --> 02:13:58.240
[Guest]: because I have seen the love and affection and the challenges that have been overcome

02:13:58.960 --> 02:14:04.800
[Guest]: by the people in Afghanistan, in Iran and Iraq who have embraced us. If not for them and not

02:14:04.800 --> 02:14:09.440
[Guest]: their feeling for oneness, this project would not have been done. That's my takeaway from it.

02:14:10.480 --> 02:14:14.960
[Guest]: And the message to my communities also is that it's the message of oneness. There's no difference,

02:14:14.960 --> 02:14:20.000
[Guest]: right? So we need to have the ability to embrace everyone. It's the need of the day. The world is

02:14:20.000 --> 02:14:25.360
[Amit Varma]: already broken up. And does that also mean being honest and self-critical and recognising the

02:14:25.360 --> 02:14:30.160
[Amit Varma]: rigidity that has crept into the faith over the last few decades? Well, every faith goes into

02:14:30.160 --> 02:14:34.800
[Guest]: all kinds of rigidity, all kinds. There's nothing new. It's not rocket science. Every faith evolves

02:14:34.800 --> 02:14:43.040
[Guest]: that way, right? Religion is a defining of a boundary around spirituality. So I am a proud

02:14:43.040 --> 02:14:48.560
[Guest]: adherent of the Khalsa tradition. I wear a turban. I keep uncut beard. I'm proud of it because of my

02:14:48.560 --> 02:14:53.760
[Guest]: culture, my history, my tradition, and I will die like this. But that's not any reason for me to not

02:14:53.760 --> 02:15:00.080
[Guest]: embrace anyone else. Your culture, a Sikh in Afghanistan may have a different culture. In my

02:15:00.080 --> 02:15:08.480
[Guest]: journey, I met Assamese Sikhs. I met Nanak Panthis of Oriya origin in Orissa, right? And they don't

02:15:08.480 --> 02:15:14.400
[Guest]: speak my Punjabi language, but yet they are believer in the faith, right? And they don't look

02:15:14.400 --> 02:15:19.920
[Guest]: like me. So who am I to pass judgment on them? It's the only thing that I've learned, right? I think

02:15:19.920 --> 02:15:25.520
[Guest]: the key message is that the need of the hour, the need of any place in the world, even within our own

02:15:25.520 --> 02:15:31.840
[Guest]: country at this point of time is that we need to learn to live with the oneness. There's a lot of

02:15:31.840 --> 02:15:37.120
[Guest]: damage that's happened to the underlying structure of the coexistence, and we need to rise above that.

02:15:37.120 --> 02:15:43.600
[Guest]: And Nanak's message in this time is very important for that. And I'm often reminded of the prayer we

02:15:43.600 --> 02:15:49.120
[Guest]: used to read in our school, in Doon School when I was there, Rabindranath take orders, right?

02:15:49.120 --> 02:15:54.080
[Amit Varma]: But the world has not been broken up by... Into fragments by narrow domestic walls.

02:15:54.080 --> 02:15:58.960
[Guest]: Yeah, into that heaven of freedom, let my country awake. I think that's the only message.

02:15:59.840 --> 02:16:04.480
[Amit Varma]: I think Nanak was striving for that. And finally, you've finished shooting most of Allegory,

02:16:04.480 --> 02:16:08.240
[Amit Varma]: which is a 30 part documentary series, but there's a lot of work left on post production.

02:16:08.240 --> 02:16:13.760
[Amit Varma]: You're going to Lahore soon to record again with Salima Khwaja. You still need to raise funds for

02:16:13.760 --> 02:16:17.920
[Amit Varma]: some of that. If any of the listeners of the show would want to contribute to your project,

02:16:18.480 --> 02:16:22.880
[Guest]: how can they do so? Where should they go? Yeah, so there is a charitable organization

02:16:23.520 --> 02:16:26.960
[Guest]: that's supporting this project within India. It's a global project. We're managing it out

02:16:26.960 --> 02:16:32.080
[Guest]: of Singapore, but we are in need for fund. These projects for five years are only running because

02:16:32.080 --> 02:16:37.600
[Guest]: of people who support us, right? And if anyone wants to support, there are ways of doing it.

02:16:37.600 --> 02:16:42.800
[Guest]: We have a tax exempt organization that's helping us as a third party organization.

02:16:43.760 --> 02:16:50.960
[Guest]: At this point, I will simply request that my email could be given and they can contact me on that.

02:16:50.960 --> 02:16:59.600
[Guest]: Or my WhatsApp, it's the Singapore number, which is plus 6598326508. They can drop me a line on

02:16:59.600 --> 02:17:03.840
[Guest]: that or they can email me and you can give my email at the bottom of the podcast.

02:17:03.840 --> 02:17:05.920
[Guest]: Both the email and the number will be in the show notes.

02:17:05.920 --> 02:17:10.640
[Guest]: Yeah. And anyone can contact me and we can take it from there. But we are looking for support.

02:17:10.640 --> 02:17:16.880
[Guest]: I mean, there are no organizations behind this project. This is a quest of a madman.

02:17:16.880 --> 02:17:23.280
[Guest]: And we have proven ourselves as a team long enough for five years that we are able to generate stuff.

02:17:24.000 --> 02:17:29.760
[Guest]: And if people who feel that there's a space for this narrative, it's not about Sikhs. It's about

02:17:29.760 --> 02:17:36.880
[Guest]: humanity. All these narratives, my books on Sikh legacy in Pakistan are about humanity and equally

02:17:36.880 --> 02:17:43.040
[Guest]: should impress and motivate any non-Sikh to delve into them. Similarly, Gunanak's message has to be

02:17:43.040 --> 02:17:47.200
[Guest]: appreciated by everyone and anyone who comes forward can reach out here.

02:17:47.200 --> 02:17:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And even if we can't exactly live in borderless geographies,

02:17:50.480 --> 02:17:54.480
[Amit Varma]: we can live in borderless minds. Thank you so much for coming on the show, Amardeep.

02:17:54.480 --> 02:17:56.480
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for giving me an opportunity. I appreciate that.

